1. d4 d5 2.
c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 (3. e3 Nf6 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 a6 {simply transposes}) 3... Nf6 4.
e3 e6 {This is by far Black's most common choice and the first important
crossroad in our repertoire. Black's main move has historically been 4...e6,
which will be the move I will be recommending. However, it should be noted
that 4...Bg4 has enjoyed a surge in popularity recently and I have employed it
numerous times as well. However, it will be outside the scope of this
repertoire. The main reason for my choice has to do with 3.e3, which I intend
to meet with 3...Nf6 (a repertoire based on 4...Bg4 would require the study of
an additional main line after 3.e3 e5) 4.Bxc4 e6 - transposing to our main
lines.} 5. Bxc4 a6 $5 {This is our first major deviation from the standard
main line. The idea of this move is to maintain as much flexibility as
possible by delaying the ...c7-c5 pawn break until Black's bishop has already
been developed to b7. The main line goes 5...c5 6.0-0 a6 and here white has a
wealth of interesting choices. Firstly, he may choose to enter a dynamic IQP
middlegame after 7.Bb3 cxd4 8.exd4 Nc6 9.Nc3 Be7 10.Bg5 0-0 11.Qd2 Na5 12.Bc2
b5 13.Rad1 leading to a position that I have studied extensively where I
conclude that White enjoys a serious initiative. Secondly, White can also
choose a more positional approach with 7.dxc5!? Qxd1 8.Rxd1 Bxc5 9.Nbd2 0-0 10.
Be2 vacates the c4-square for the knight and leads to a surprisingly
unpleasant endgame for Black. It is mainly due to these two lines that I have
decided to avoid 5...c5 in favour of 5...a6.} 6. O-O b5 {White can (and should)
force Black to advance his pawn to b4 with} 7. Bd3 {This is the most
aggressive and principled move. White intends to undermine Black's queenside
by means of a2-a4 and thus provoke the weakening of the c4-square after black
is forced to advance his b-pawn. Moreover (and unlike 7.Bb3) White keeps an
eye on the e4-square to support a timely e3-e4 advance. This move was
recommended by Avrukh in his excellent book "Grandmaster Repertoire 1.d4" 
(2008).} Bb7 8. a4 ({The continuation} 8. Qe2 Nbd7 9. Rd1 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11.
a4 b4 12. Nbd2 {transposes}) 8... b4 9. Nbd2 ({White can also avoid the IQP
positions and instead push his e-pawn all the way to e5 with} 9. Qe2 $5 c5 10.
dxc5 ({White should be careful not to push too hard here} 10. e4 $6 cxd4 11. e5
Nfd7 12. Bg5 ({After} 12. Nbd2 Nc5 13. Nc4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Bc5 15. Bf4 Qd5 {
Black is doing very well.}) 12... Qc7 13. Nbd2 Nc5 14. Rfc1 ({Nothing changes} 
14. Rac1 Nc6) 14... Nc6 15. Nc4 Nb3 $17) (10. Nbd2 {- transposes to 9.Nbd2})
10... Bxc5 11. e4 (11. Rd1 Nbd7 12. Nbd2 Qc7 (12... Qb8 $5) 13. Nb3 (13. b3 Nd5
14. Bb2 Nc3 15. Bxc3 bxc3 16. Nc4 Bb4 $15 {0-1 (38) Bykhovsky,A (2453)-Zifroni,
D (2501) Tel Aviv 1999}) 13... Bd5 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. Bd2 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qb7 $15
{0-1 (36) Basescu,N-Adianto,U (2535) Philadelphia 1994}) 11... Nbd7 12. Nbd2 a5
13. e5 Nd5 14. Ne4 {White will now pick up black's dark-squared bishop. The
question for black becomes how best to part with it} Be7 ({Worse is} 14... h6
$6 {when White can go for} 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb5+ Nd7 (16... Ke7 17. Be3 Nxe3
18. Qxe3 Qb6 19. Nd2 $16) (16... Kf8 17. Be3 $16) 17. Qe4 $14 {White is better
due to his space advantage and Black's vulnerable king. The possibility of Qg4
is always in the air.}) ({It seems that after} 14... Qb6 $5 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16.
Be3 (16. Bb5+ Bc6 $11) 16... Nxe3 17. Bb5+ Bc6 18. Bxc6+ Qxc6 19. Qxe3 Nxa4 20.
Rfc1 Qb5 21. Ng5 $44 {White has a decent compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Bg5
O-O 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. g3 (17. Nd6 $6 Nf4 18. Bxh7+ (18. Qe3 $2 Nxd3 19. Qxd3
Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Nxe5 $19) 18... Kxh7 19. Qc2+ Kg8 20. Nxb7 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Qxb7 $15
) 17... N5b6 $1 {By clearing the long diagonal the white knight cannot jump to
d6 since Black would capture on f3 and then e5} 18. Qe3 h6 19. Rfc1 Bd5 20. Bb5
Rac8 $11) 9... c5 10. Qe2 {This is by far the move I encounter the most in
practice. White's idea is to take on an isolated pawn, which will provide some
attacking chances on the kingside and a clamp-on c5, which coupled with a4-a5,
increase White's control on the queenside. And what is perhaps most important,
White will finally solve the problem of his c1-bishop since it will find a
very comfortable home on the g5-square - transposes to 9.Nbd2} (10. e4 {
This is another way to get a pawn to e5, thus driving the knight away from f6
and creating attacking chances on the kingside} Nc6 $1 {Black's queenside
knight is a superfluous piece. The idea of this move is to capture on d4 with
the knight and trade it off. If Black were to take on d4 directly, then it
will be difficult to find a good square for the b8-knight, as the following
lines illustrate} (10... cxd4 $6 11. e5 Nfd7 12. Nc4 Nc6 (12... Nc5 13. Bg5 Qc7
14. Rc1 Nbd7 15. Nxd4 $16) 13. Bg5 Qb8 14. Re1 $16 {the knight on c6 blocks
the bishop and Black will have a hard time developing the kingside as well})
11. e5 (11. d5 $2 exd5 12. exd5 Qxd5 $17) 11... Nd7 {It is of fundamental
importance to retreat the knight to d7. It might be tempting to place the
knight on d5, but this will only serve to block the bishop. The best square
for the knight is actually c5, from where it will put pressure on White's
weakened queenside, particularly the b3-square} 12. Be4 $1 {stopping black
idea of capturing with the knight on d4} (12. Ne4 {White allows the capture on
d4, but at least the c5-square is under control} Nxd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Bg5 Qa5
15. f4 Qd5 16. Qe2 (16. Rc1 $6 Nc5 $132) 16... Nc5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 $15 {and
Black was doing well in the game Theodorou, N (2450) -Halkias, S (2543)
Paleochora GRE 2016}) (12. Nc4 $6 {this is a particularly careless move since
aside from allowing the capture on d4 it allows Black to put a knight on c5}
Nxd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Qg4 Nc5 {[%csl Gc5] this is a dream position for Black.
Despite the lag in kingside development, White's queenside is in shambles and
it's not clear how White will get his pawn back.} 15. Rd1 h5 16. Qg3 h4 17. Qg4
h3 $17 {0-1 (47) Huhndorf, A (2264) -Karpatchev,A (2483) Bad Woerishofen GER
2010}) 12... cxd4 {Black has not been able to trade off the knight on c6, but
now prepares to make use of the c5-square} 13. Nc4 ({White can fight for c5
with} 13. Nb3 $5 Nc5 (13... Qb6 $5 {is also playable but I'm not convinced the
queen will be well placed here. In fact, the queen usually finds itself more
useful along the d-file (either on d7 or d5)}) 14. Bg5 ({Another option is} 14.
Nxc5 {when after} Bxc5 15. Bf4 {Black should go for} Na5 ({A typical trap
would be} 15... O-O $2 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Ng5+ Kg8 18. Qh5 $18 {White is
winning.}) 16. Bxb7 Nxb7 {After the exchange of the light-squared bishops,
White's attack is not dangerous. As an example, you can take a look at the
following line:} 17. Qd3 Qd5 18. Rac1 h6 (18... O-O 19. Ng5 $40) 19. Rfd1 O-O
20. Nd2 Rfd8 21. Ne4 Bf8 $15 {The activity of White's pieces does not provide
enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Qd7 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Rc1 Bb6 17. Qd2
h6 18. Bh4 O-O 19. Bb1 Bd8 (19... Ne7 $5 20. Qxb4 (20. Qd3 Ng6 $17) 20... Nd5
21. Qd2 Qxa4 $15) 20. Bg3 Ne7 21. Qxb4 Bxf3 22. gxf3 a5 23. Qb3 Qa7 24. Qc2 Nf5
$15 {1/2-1/2 (70) Grachev,B (2660)-Fier,A (2571) Moscow 2011}) 13... Nc5 $1 ({
In his "Grandmaster Repertoire 1.d4" (2008) Avrukh only mentions} 13... Rc8 $6
14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Rc1 Bc5 16. Bf4 Qb8 17. Qd3 h6 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 19. Nxd4 Bxa4 20.
b3 Bc6 21. Nxc6 Rxc6 22. Rfd1 Qc8 23. Be3 $18 {stating that White has a
powerful initiative. This, in fact, is an understatement since White's
position is practically winning}) 14. Bg5 (14. Bxc6+ Bxc6 15. Nxd4 Bb7 $15 {
[%cal Gd8d5]}) 14... Qc7 15. Bxc6+ Qxc6 $1 {Black is willing to part with his
light-squared bishop, but only for the knight on c4 (not the one on f3) since
that knight can otherwise head for the d6-outpost. By recapturing with the
queen Black keeps the white knight glued to f3} (15... Bxc6 $6 16. Nxd4 Bd5 17.
Rc1 $16 {[%cal Gc4d6]}) 16. Na5 (16. Rc1 a5 17. Re1 (17. Qxd4 $2 Nb3 $17 {
illustrates the chronical weakness of the b3-square}) 17... h6 18. Bf4) (16.
Qxd4 $2 Nb3 $17) 16... Qc7 17. Nxb7 Qxb7 18. Nxd4 {White has managed to get
the knight to d4, but since there is no longer a knight on c4 all the Nd6
ideas are gone} h6 19. Be3 (19. Bh4 Qe4 $1 (19... g5 $5 20. Bg3 Rd8 $17) 20.
Bg3 Rd8 $19 {[%csl Rd4]}) (19. Qh5 Qe4 $1 20. Be3 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) 19...
Rd8 (19... Be7 $5 20. Qg4 g6 21. Rfc1 h5 22. Qe2 O-O 23. Rc4 Rfd8 24. Rac1 Rd5
$11 {[%cal Ga8d8] also looks fine for Black}) 20. Rc1 (20. Qg4 Rd5 21. f4 g6
22. Rfd1 Be7 $15 {Black completes his development and enjoys the better
coordination}) 20... Rd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] The d5-square is a key pivot point for
Black's pieces and an ideal square for the black rook to support the knight on
c5 and prepare a doubling along the d-file} (20... Qe4 $6 21. Rc4 Qxe5 22. Qc1
$36) (20... Be7 21. Qg4 Qe4 22. Qxg7) 21. Rc4 (21. Qg4 g6 {doesn't seem to
change much}) 21... Be7 22. Qg4 g6 23. Rfc1 O-O $1 (23... h5 24. Qf3 O-O 25.
Rxc5 $18) 24. Bxh6 Rfd8 $132 {0-1 (38) Fish, G (2460) -Postny,E (2658) Skopje
MKD 2015}) (10. Nc4 cxd4 11. exd4 Be7 12. a5 Nbd7 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Nfe5 {
- 10.Qe2}) (10. Nb3 $6 cxd4 11. exd4 Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Bf4 Bd5 {highlights
the misplacement of the knight on b3}) (10. a5 cxd4 11. exd4 Be7 12. Nc4 Nbd7
13. Qe2 O-O 14. Nfe5 {- 10.Qe2}) ({Taking on an isolated pawn and weakening
the c3-square is not a good combination for white} 10. b3 $6 cxd4 11. exd4 (11.
Nxd4 $2 e5 $19) 11... Be7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Nc4 Nd5 $132 {[%csl Rc3]}) 10... cxd4
11. exd4 Be7 12. a5 {Fixing the a6-pawn is an important idea in this variation.
} ({After} 12. Nc4 {Black can play} a5 $5 {himself.}) 12... O-O 13. Nc4 Nbd7
14. Bf4 {This is a strange place to put the bishop (certainly not my top
choice), but according to my database it is the main line. Black seems to
achieve a very comfortable position after} ({After} 14. Nfe5 $5 {Black should
probably delay the exchange of the e5-knight and play} Nd5 (14... Nxe5 $6 15.
dxe5 Nd5 (15... Nd7 16. Qg4) 16. Qe4 g6 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Rad1 Rc8 19. Qg4 Rc5
20. h4 $16 {1/2-1/2 (43) Barsov,A (2497)-Kortschnoj,V (2568) Montreal 2004})
15. Bd2 Rc8 16. Rfe1 Rc7 17. Rac1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bc5 $13 {Black's active minor
pieces compensate White's space advantage. The position remains balanced.}) (
14. Bd2 {the idea behind this move is to follow up with Rfc1 and Nce5. After
these moves White will have serious pressure on the queenside} Bd5 $5 {the
idea of placing the bishop on d5 and later the queen ob b7 is thematic in the
QGA. It also allows Black to eliminate the knight on c4 if it threatens to
come to d6. So this ...Bd5 idea is a good tool to keep in mind.} 15. Rfc1 ({
After} 15. Nfe5 {Black can force favourable simplifications. For example:} Nxe5
(15... Qb8 16. Bg5 $36) 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. Bf4 Bxc4 18. Bxc4 Qc7 19. Rfc1 Qb7 20.
Qg4 Rfd8 $13 {Black has nothing to worry about. At some point, White's
far-advanced pawns on e5 and a5 can become a weakness. In this structure,
Black often protects the kingside by means of the maneuver Nf8-g6.}) 15... Qb8
16. Nce5 (16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 Qb7 $13) 16... Qb7 $11 {the queenside is under
control and Black has good pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal}) (14. Nce5 Nxe5
15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Be4 (16. Bb1 Nc5 $15) 16... Qc7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11) 14... Nd5
15. Bg3 N7f6 16. Nfd2 g6 $1 {Black prepares active counterplay on the
queenside by means of ...Nh5 followed by ...Nf4} 17. Be5 (17. Nb3 Nh5 18. Qd2
Rc8 $15 19. Rac1 $2 Bg5 20. f4 {1/2-1/2 (57) Dumitrache,D (2395)-Baburin,A 
(2520) Cappelle-la-Grande 1994} Nhxf4 $1 21. Bxf4 Nxf4 22. Rxf4 e5 23. Nxe5 Qd5
24. Rcf1 Bxf4 25. Qxf4 Qxb3 $19) (17. Ne3 Nh5 $1 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Be4 Nxg3 20.
hxg3 Qd7 $15 {1/2-1/2 (75) Soppe,G (2455)-Slipak,S (2510) Villa Gesell 1998})
17... Nh5 (17... Nd7 $5) 18. Be4 f6 (18... Rc8 19. Nb6 $16 {1-0 (32) Kuzubov,Y
(2626)-Kunin,V (2546) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2009}) (18... Ndf4 19. Qf3
Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Nd5 21. Nc5 $14) 19. Bg3 Ndf4 (19... f5 $5 20. Bf3 f4 21. Qxe6+
Kh8 $13) 20. Bxf4 (20. Qf3 Bxe4 21. Nxe4 f5 22. Nc5 Qxd4 23. Nb6 Bxc5 24. Nxa8
e5 $44) 20... Nxf4 21. Qf3 Bxe4 22. Qxf4 Bd5 $13 *

