1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3.
Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O b5 7. Be2 $5 {This is White's most solid
choice and in my opinion an underrated move. In fact, it is the move I often
recommend my students in order to get an easy game with a clear middlegame
plan, even if this means Black can equalize eventually.} Bb7 8. a4 (8. b3 {
will usually end up transposing to the main line since if White does not play
a4 his minor pieces (especially the knight on d2) will feel restricted without
access to the c4-square} Nbd7 9. Bb2 c5 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Rc1 (11. a4 b4 {
transposes}) 11... O-O (11... Rc8 $5 {can be considered if Black wants to
avoid getting his pawns doubled on the kingside.}) 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Bxf6 gxf6
14. Nd4 Rc8 15. Bf3 Qd7 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11 {was by no means worse for Black in
the game Sargsyan, A (2339)-Harikrishna, P (2730) Pro Chess League 2019}) 8... b4
9. b3 ({As you've probably noticed by now, there are an endless amount of move
orders and transpositions. Why can delay the queenside fianchetto and
accelerate the idea of getting the bishop to f3. However, our play is usually
thematic (as opposed to forced), so we can meet this idea in the same fashion} 
9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. Nc4 c5 11. Nfe5 Be7 12. Bf3 Qc7 13. b3 cxd4 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15.
Bb2 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 O-O 17. Bxd4 Bf6 $11 {Black trades off the bishops and
starts to aim for the c3-square}) 9... Nbd7 10. Bb2 c5 11. Nbd2 Be7 12. Nc4 (
12. Rc1 O-O 13. dxc5 (13. Nc4 {leads to a similar position as the main line 
but allows Black an additional option} cxd4 $5 (13... Bd5) 14. Qxd4 Nc5 15.
Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Na5 Bd5 $132 {gave Black the typical counterplay against the
weak b3-pawn in the game Goldin, A (2540)-Dlugy, M (2518) Saint Louis 2019})
13... Nxc5 $1 {in general Black should strive to recapture on c5 with the
knight since this will put much-needed pressure on b3} (13... Bxc5 14. Ne5 Rc8
15. Bf3 Nd5 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Nc4 $14 {Aronian,L (2793)-Caruana,F (2808)
Stavanger 2017}) 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nd4 Rc8 16. Bf3 Bd5 17. Qe2 f5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5
19. Nc4 Qb7 $13 {Black's doubled pawns are not weak at all. In fact, black
went on to win in the game Matthias, H (2386)-Jonkman, H (2372) NRW 2000}) 12...
O-O ({If Black wants to take on d4, then he should do it before White places a
knight on e5} 12... cxd4 $5 13. Qxd4 (13. Nxd4 Nc5 $132 {xb3}) (13. Bxd4 O-O
14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Nfe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Ne4 $132 {xc3}) 13... O-O 14. Rfd1 Nc5 15.
Qf4 Bd5 16. Nd4 Rc8 $13) 13. Nfe5 {This is the critical position of the 7.Be2
line. White's idea is to play Bf3 and trade off black's powerful b7-bishop. If
he is able to accomplish this, then Black's weaknesses on the queenside will
begin to tell thanks to the powerful knight on c4. Black's main idea in these
positions is to create pressure against White's main (if only) weaknesses: the
b3-pawn and the c3-square. This can be accomplished with moves like ...Nc5, ...
Bd5 and the manoeuvre...Ne4-c3, respectively. So the thematic move here is} (
13. a5 cxd4 $1 {now White does not dispose of the Nxd7 in-between move, so the
f6-knight will not be diverted and can head for the c3-square right away} 14.
Bxd4 (14. Nxd4 Ne4 15. Bf3 Qc7 16. Rc1 Ndc5 17. Nb6 Rad8 $11) 14... Ne4 $132 {
[%cal Ge7f6,Gd8e7]}) (13. Rc1 cxd4 {transposes to 12.Rc1}) 13... Bd5 $1 {
[%csl Rd8][%cal Ge7f6,Gd8e7] Black has tried some other ways of carrying out
this same idea, but I believe the direct approach to be the most accurate.
Black's main concern is finding a good square for the queen, and by far the
best seems to be the e7 square. Below are some good examples of the kind of
positions White is aiming for and which we would like to avoid. Mainly, we
should stay away from middlegames and endgames where White is left with a
knight on c4 against our dark-squared bishop.} ({Black can also try to go for
the c3-square right away with} 13... cxd4 $5 14. Nxd7 $1 {this is a thematic
in-between move when black takes on d4, forcing the Black knight back to d7
and away from the c3-square} (14. Bxd4 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Ne4 $132 {[%csl Gc3][%cal
Ge7f6,Ge4c3]}) 14... Nxd7 (14... Qxd7 15. Bxd4 {[%cal Rc4b6]} (15. Nb6 $2 Qc6
$19) 15... Rad8 16. Rc1 Nd5 17. Bf3 Bf6 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Qxd7 Rxd7 20. Bxb7
Rxb7 21. Na5 $16 {leads to the type of endgames where Black will get tortured})
15. Bxd4 Bd5 $1 {is the same idea as in the main line} (15... Bc5 $6 {this is
not the best way of going about the bishop trade} 16. Bb2 Qc7 17. Bf3 Rfd8 18.
Bxb7 Qxb7 19. Qg4 Bf8 20. Bd4 $14 {the bishop on d4 dominates the d7-knight
and prevents any kind of counterplay against the b3-pawn, as was seen in the
game Holm, K (2403)-Shabalov, A (2549) Helsingor 2017}) (15... Bf6 {would
normally be Black's standard follow-up, but here it allows White to place the
knight on a5} 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Na5 $14 {[%csl Ga5] it's hard
to overemphasize how important the a5-square is in this variation. This is a
perfect example of the kind of position White is hoping for}) 16. a5 Bf6 17.
Bxf6 (17. Nb6 Nxb6 18. Bxb6 Qe7 19. Rc1 Bc3 $11 {the position is balanced
since the weakness of the a6-pawn is offset by the weak b3-pawn}) 17... Qxf6 (
17... Nxf6 18. Nb6 $16) 18. Qd2 (18. Nb6 Nxb6 19. axb6 a5 $11) 18... Qe7 19.
Rfd1 (19. f3 Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Ne5 21. Rfc1 Rfd8 $15 {This is the kind of
middlegame (knight vs light-squared bishop) that Black is looking for. White's
position is already delicate.}) 19... Rfd8 20. Qb2 Rab8 {[%cal Gd7c5] With
equality.} ({Also possible is} 20... Bxc4 21. Bxc4 Nc5 {with a good play on
the dark squares.})) ({Taking on e5 also poses some serious strategic dangers,
since it provides White with a powerful outpost on d6} 13... Nxe5 $6 14. dxe5
$1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc4d6]} Nd5 15. Qc2 Qc7 16. Rac1 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Rac8 (17...
a5 18. Nd6 $16) 18. a5 Qb8 (18... Bc6 19. Nd6 $16) 19. Bf3 Bc6 (19... Qa8 20.
Nd6 $16) 20. Nd6 $16) ({I don't think it's generally advisable to place the
pawn on a5. The pawn is actually weaker there, as well as the b5-square} 13...
a5 $6 14. Bf3 Qc7 15. Rc1 Rfd8 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Qf3 Qxf3 18. gxf3 $14 {
[%csl Ra5] and the a-pawn suffers}) 14. Rc1 {White tries to make it hard for
our queen to reach its desired square. This is White's most natural move and
the one I have faced the most in practice} (14. a5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Rc4a5]
Black should have mixed feelings about this move since even though it clamps
down on our queenside, it also allows our queen to get to b7 without having to
fear a possible Na5. Nevertheless, Black can still choose where to put the
queen. Below I examine both possibilities} cxd4 (14... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gc7b7]
Black may consider the additional possibility of placing the queen on b7 when
White has placed a pawn on a5 since White will no longer be able to use this
square for his knight to harass the queen.} 15. Rc1 ({After} 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16.
dxc5 Nxc5 {Black doesn't face problems. For example:} (16... Qb7 $6 17. e4 (17.
Nb6 $5) 17... Bxe4 18. Nd6 Bxd6 19. Qxd6 Rfc8 20. Rfd1 Bd5 21. Rac1 $14 {
0-1 (90) Murshed,N (2436)-Postny,E (2592) Chennai 2011}) 17. Nb6 Rad8 18. Nxd5
Rxd5 19. Qc2 Rfd8 20. Bd4 e5 21. Bxc5 Rxc5 22. Bc4 g6 $11) 15... Qb7 {[%csl
Gb7] the queen has reached its target square} ({To a strategically dangerous
position leads} 15... Nxe5 $6 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. f4 Rad8 18. Qc2 Nb8 19. e4 $36 {
[%cal Gf4f5] With a dangerous attack to follow.}) {The only drawback of
Black's concept is that White can build the central barrier f3-e4, this
restricting Black's light-squared bishop and f6-knight.} 16. dxc5 {This is the
most precise move order.} ({Starting with} 16. f3 {is not precise. Black can
play} Rfd8 17. e4 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 cxd4 19. Bxd4 Nf8 $15 {and White has serious
problems along the d-file}) ({Harmless is} 16. Bf3 {when after} Rad8 17. Qe2 {
Black can invite massive simplifications. For example:} Nxe5 ({Another
sensible option is} 17... cxd4 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Bxd4 Qb5 $132) 18. dxe5 Bxf3
19. Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Nd7 21. Rfd1 Nb8 22. Nd6 (22. Kf1 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rd8 $15
{[%csl Ra5]}) 22... Bxd6 23. exd6 Nd7 $15 {Black is already better in this
endgame. The d6-pawn is more vulnerable than the one on c5. A possible plan
for Black would be ...Rc8-c6 followed by ...f7-f6, and Kf7-e6.}) 16... Nxc5 17.
f3 Rfd8 18. Qc2 Rac8 19. Bd4 Ncd7 20. Qb2 $14 {White keeps a slight advantage
but the position is playable for Black.}) 15. Nxd7 $1 (15. Qxd4 Nc5 $132) (15.
Bxd4 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 (16. Nxe5 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Ge4c3]}) 16... Nd7 17. Bd4 Bf6 18.
Qd2 Qe7 $11) 15... Nxd7 (15... Qxd7 $6 16. Nb6 Qb7 17. Nxa8 Rxa8 18. Qxd4 Bxg2
19. Rfc1 $16) 16. Bxd4 Bf6 17. Qd2 Qe7 {[%csl Ge7] the queen has reached it
target square} 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. Rac1 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Nc5 21. Qb2 Bb7 $11) (14.
Bf3 {an interesting move since it prevents us from carrying out our normal
plan (...cxd4 followed by ...Bf6)} Qc7 {Once again we see the queen coming to
c7, not as a rule but rather as an exception since the normal manoeuvre to
reach e7 does not work here} (14... cxd4 $6 15. Nxd7 $1 Nxd7 16. Bxd5 exd5 17.
Qxd4 Bf6 18. Qxd5 $16) 15. Rc1 ({The main point of putting the bishop on d5
can be appreciated after} 15. Bxd5 $2 exd5 16. Nd2 (16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Nd2 c4
$17) 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 $15) 15... Rac8 (15... Qb7 16. Na5 $16) 16. Nxd7 (
16. dxc5 Nxc5 $132) 16... Nxd7 17. Nd2 (17. a5 Qb7 $11) (17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Nd2
Bf6 19. Rc2 Qb7 20. dxc5 Bxb2 21. Rxb2 Rxc5 22. Nf3 Rfc8 $11 {Black's control
over the c-file (and the c3-outpost in particular) amply compensate for
Black's isolated pawn on d5}) (17. Qe2 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 cxd4 19. Bxd4 Bf6 20. Rfd1
Rfd8 $11) 17... Qb7 18. e4 Bc6 19. Qe2 cxd4 20. Bxd4 Bf6 $1 {this is one of
Black's most useful maneuvers. By trading off the dark-squared bishops white
loses control over the c3-square} (20... e5 21. Be3 Rfd8 22. Nc4 $14) (20...
Rfd8 21. Nc4 $14) 21. Bxf6 (21. e5 Bxf3 22. Nxf3 Be7 23. Nd2 Rfd8 24. Nc4 Nc5
25. Bxc5 Rxc5 26. Rfd1 Rcd5 27. Rxd5 Qxd5 $15) 21... Nxf6 22. Rfe1 Rfd8 23. Nc4
Qa7 24. e5 Bxf3 25. Qxf3 Nd5 26. Nd6 Rc3 $132 {Black has invaded c3 and is
able to counter-balance the knight on d6}) 14... cxd4 {With the rook on c1 it
will be even harder for the queen to reach the b7-square. Therefore, we must
resume our journey to e7. Moreover, when Black is intending to take on e5, it
is important he plays this move first. Otherwise, White will recapture on e5
with a pawn and get a powerful outpost on d6} (14... Qc7 $6 15. Bf3 Qb7 16. Na5
Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qc7 18. Nec6 $16) (14... Nxe5 $6 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Nd6 $36 {
[%csl Gd6]}) 15. Nxd7 $1 {As we have seen several times by now, this is
White's thematic response to ...cxd4. The point is to drive the black knight
away from the e4 or d5 squares that might give it access to c3} (15. Bxd4 Rc8
16. Nxd7 ({То а complete equality leads} 16. a5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxa5 18. Ra1
Qc7 19. Bxa6 Ra8 $11) ({In case of} 16. Bf3 {Black once again goes for massive
exchanges. After} Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Rxc1 18. Qxc1 Bxf3 (18... Bxb3 19. Nc6 $16) 19.
Nxf3 Qd5 20. Qc2 Ne4 21. Rd1 Rd8 $132 {the position seems to be equal. Note
that in some cases Black can even overtake the initiative by means of ...f7-f6
followed by ...e6-e5.}) 16... Nxd7 17. a5 Bf6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 (18... Nxf6 19. Nb6
$16) 19. Qd2 Qe7 20. Nb6 Nxb6 21. axb6 Rb8 $11) ({In response to} 15. Qxd4 {
Black has the thematic} Nc5 {making use of the weak b3-pawn.} 16. Qd1 a5 (16...
Nfe4 $5 17. f3 Nc3 18. Bxc3 bxc3 19. Rxc3 Qc7 $44) 17. f3 (17. Bf3 {is well
met by} Nfe4) 17... Qc7 18. e4 Bb7 $11 {White has managed to build his central
pawn construction but he lacks stability mainly due to the weak b3-pawn.})
15... Nxd7 16. Bxd4 (16. Qxd4 Bf6 17. Qd2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Qg5 19. g3 a5 $11)
16... Bf6 $1 {Once again we encounter this maneuver, after which Black has no
real problems} (16... Rc8 17. Qd2 Nc5 18. Qb2 Bf6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6
21. Nb6 Rc7 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Rc2 a5 24. Bf3 Rfc8 25. Bxd5 $16 {0-1 (50)
Gelfand,B (2741)-Karjakin,S (2760) Moscow 2010}) 17. Bf3 (17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Bf3
Rc8 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 $15 {[%cal Gd5c3]}) (17. a5 Bxc4 18. Rxc4 Qxa5 $15) (17. f3
e5 18. Bb2 Be6 19. e4 Nc5 $15 (19... a5 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5]})) 17... Bxd4 18. Qxd4
Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Qh5 $132 *

