1. d4 d5
2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O b5 7. Bb3 {I believe this
move is considerably weaker than 7.Bd3, as it neither pressures the b5-pawn
nor supports the central pawn advance. Moreover, this move order allows Black
an interesting idea.} Bb7 $5 {Our non-standard move-order allows us the
possibility of keeping our pawn on b5, thus avoiding the weakening of the
c4-square} ({The traditional main line (by transposition of moves) arises after
} 7... c5 8. a4 b4 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. e4 $5 (10. Nc4 Nbd7 11. a5 Be7 12. Ba4 O-O
13. Qe2 Qc7 14. Bd2 Bd5 15. Rfc1 Qb7 $11 {is the typical position Black is
aiming for in this variation: 0-1 (32) Cebalo,M (2527)-Horvath,A (2528) Davos
2004}) (10. a5 Be7 11. Ba4+ Nbd7 12. dxc5 Qc7 13. Nb3 O-O 14. Bd2 Nxc5 $11) (
10. Qe2 Be7 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Bd2 Nbd7 $11 {0-1 (32) Jussupow,A 
(2640)-Anand,V (2765) Dortmund 1997}) 10... Be7 11. e5 Nfd7 12. Nc4 (12. Re1
O-O 13. Ne4 cxd4 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd7c5]}) (12. Qe2 Nc6 $132) 12... O-O {
this is the critical position, beyond the scope of this survey. However, my
impression is that Black is worse} 13. Bf4 (13. Nd6) (13. Bc2) (13. Be3)) 8.
Qe2 (8. a4 Nbd7 9. Qe2 c5 10. axb5 ({After} 10. Rd1 {Black should play} Qb8 {
As we are going to witness on many occasions, b8 is a perfect spot for the
queen. From this position, the queen escapes possible dangerous oppositions
and indirectly protects the b5-pawn.} 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Nc3 (13.
dxc5 Nxc5 14. Bc2 Bd6 $11 {0-1 (55) Mensch,E (2348)-Guliyev, N (2590) France
2007}) 13... c4 ({After} 13... b4 14. Na4 Be7 15. e4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {Black
cannot complete the development because of the vulnerability of the e6-pawn.}
Nxe4 {0-1 (26) Namgilov,S (2425) -Ibragimov,I (2580) Elista 1995} 17. Nxe6 $1
fxe6 18. Bxe6 $36) 14. Bc2 b4 15. Na4 Bxf3 $1 {An important exhcange allowing
Black to develop his dark-squared bishop with a tempo. For example, after} 16.
Qxf3 Bd6 17. Qc6 O-O 18. Qxc4 Bxh2+ 19. Kf1 Bd6 20. e4 Rc8 21. Qe2 Bf4 $11 {
The position is equal.}) 10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 {The weakness of the b5-pawn
is offset by the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal} 12. Nc3 (12. Qxb5 $6 cxd4 (
12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qxf3 $132) 13. exd4 (13. Nxd4 $2 Bxg2 14. Rd1 Bc5 $17)
13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qxf3 (14... Bd6 $5) 15. Bd1 Qd5 $15) 12... b4 13. Nb5 (13.
Na4 $2 Ba6 $19) (13. Nb1 Bd6 $15) 13... Qa5 $5 {This is neither the engine's
top choice nor the most popular move. However, it is more active than ...Qb8
and} 14. e4 (14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. e4 (16. Nd6+ $6 {a slight
innacuracy since White can get this position with an extra tempo} Bxd6 17. exd6
Ba6 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 O-O $13) 16... Bc6 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. exd6 Bb5 19. Bc4
Bxc4 20. Qxc4 O-O $13 {leads to a typical middlegame where the knight is an
ideal blockader and generally better than the bishop}) 14... Be7 (14... Nxe4
15. Ng5 Nxg5 16. Bxg5 $18 {[%cal Rb3e6]}) (14... Bxe4 $2 15. Bf4 $18 {[%cal
Rb5c7]}) 15. e5 (15. d5 $2 exd5 16. exd5 O-O 17. Qxe7 Re8 18. Qd6 Qxb5 $17)
15... Nd5 (15... Ne4 16. Rd1 (16. Bc2 Bc6 17. Bxe4 Qxb5 18. Qc2 c4 $15 {
0-1 (36) Uhlmann,W-Benko,P Buenos Aires 1960}) 16... O-O 17. d5 $14) 16. Bg5
Bc6 (16... Ba6 $5 {should be similar}) 17. Nd6+ (17. Bc4 O-O 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19.
Nd6 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Qxe5 $17) 17... Bxd6 18. exd6 Bb5 19. Bc4 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 O-O
$11 {Black has solved all the opening problems and retains two promising
knights}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nc3 c5 10. Rd1 Qb8 11. d5 {White has two main ideas in
this position. In the main line, we will consider what happens when White plays
for the d5-push and in the sidelines, we will see how White can go about
preparing the e3-e4 push. For the latter White will usually need to take on c5
first, otherwise, Black will take on d4 and lure the knight away from f3. As
we'll see this can have some negative implications for White.} ({I am
sceptical about this push since it weakens the dark-squares} 11. e4 cxd4 12.
Nxd4 (12. Nd5 {is a flashy move, but all smoke and mirrors in the end} Bd6 $1 (
12... exd5 $5 13. exd5+ Be7 14. Re1 O-O 15. Qxe7 Re8 $11 {also looks
completely fine for Black.}) 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Bg5 (14. Rxd4 Bc5 15. Rd1 Nxe4
16. Be3 O-O $17 {0-1 (34) Makoveev,I (2299)-Vorobiov,E (2560) St Petersburg
2019}) 14... Nxe4 15. Rxd4 h6 16. Rxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 hxg5 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19.
Qxe6+ Kf8 20. Qf5+ Kg8 21. Qe6+ $11) 12... Bd6 13. g3 O-O 14. f3 (14. f4 $6 b4
15. e5 bxc3 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. bxc3 Qc7 $15 {White's open king was decisive in
the game Jussupow, A (2595)-Khenkin, I (2610) Nordhorn 2005}) (14. a3 Rd8 15. f3
Bc5 16. Be3 Ne5 $11 {looks phenomenal for Black.}) 14... Bc5 {once g2-g3 has
been provoked then the bishop should be relocated to c5} 15. Be3 Qa7 16. Rd2
Rfd8 17. Rad1 Ne5 18. Kg2 Rd7 19. a3 Qb6 20. Nc2 Rad8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (27)
Rodriguez,J (2544)-Gutsche,D (2505) IECG email 2002}) (11. h3 {This move
prevents Black's ideas based on ...Ng4 but has an important positional
drawback. Usually, when White plays e3-e4, Black is trying to exchange the
dark-squared bishops via the f4-square. Having already played h2-h3, it will
be much more difficult to further weaken the kingside with g2-g3.} Bd6 12. Bc2
cxd4 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. e4 Nc5 {since White did not place his pawn on g3, then
the bishop can stay along the h2-b8 diagonal} 15. a3 Be5 $15) ({As usual, the
early} 11. Ne5 {leads to simplifications and easy play for Black.} Bd6 12. Nxd7
Nxd7 13. Qh5 O-O 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $5 (14... Nf6 15. Qh4 Bxc5 $11 {0-1 (34)
Bringsken,P (2100)-Winiger,A (2364) GER email 2008}) 15. Bc2 g6 16. Qh4 b4 $15)
(11. Bc2 {this is perhaps the best way of preparing e3-e4 since this advance
should be preceded by dxc5} Bd6 12. dxc5 Bxc5 (12... Nxc5 13. e4 $14) 13. h3
O-O 14. e4 Bd6 {Black should feel no problems retreating the bishop back to d6.
Control over e5 is of great importance} 15. a3 Ne5 16. Bg5 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Bh2+
18. Kh1 Be5 $15 {0-1 (51) Rozier,D (2126)-Grabner,H (2309) ICCF email 2013}) (
11. dxc5 {looks premature} Bxc5 12. e4 O-O 13. Bc2 (13. h3 b4 14. Na4 Bxe4 $17)
13... Qc7 14. h3 Rac8 15. a3 Bd6 16. Be3 Ne5 $11 {again Black clamps down on
the dark-squares.}) 11... c4 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Bc2 Bd6 $13 {leads to a dynamic
position that GM Ildar Ibragimov has demonstrated in several games to be quite
good for Black. For example,} 14. Ng5 ({The move} 14. e4 {gives Black enough
time to complete the development and coordinate his forces.} O-O 15. h3 (15.
Bg5 Ng4 16. h3 Nge5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Be3 Qc7 19. Rd2 Bc5 $15 {0-1 (54)
Mirzoev,A (2463)-Ibragimov,I (2571) Ubeda 2001}) 15... Qc7 16. Be3 Rae8 $15 {
0-1 (50) Postl,A (2315)-Ibragimov,I (2580) Graz 1995. Black is already
slightly better. He has good control over the centre, the semi-open f-file,
and space advantage on the queenside.}) ({Too passive is} 14. h3 O-O 15. e4 (
15. Ng5 Nc5 16. e4 h6 17. Nf3 b4 $36) 15... Qc7 16. a3 Rae8 17. Be3 Ne5 18. Nd4
Ng6 $13 {Black has more than enough counterplay. As we have already pointed
out, the advance h2-h3 weakens the diagonal h2-b8 and the f4-square.}) 14...
O-O $1 (14... Nc5 15. f4 Qc7 16. b4 $1 $36 {1-0 (48) Hoi,C (2435)-Borge,N 
(2455) Denmark 1996}) 15. h3 (15. Nxe6 Re8 16. Ng5 Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Bd6 $15) (15.
f4 h6 16. Nxe6 Re8 17. Bf5 Nf8 18. Nxf8 Kxf8 19. Qf2 Bc5 $44) 15... Nc5 16. f4
(16. e4 h6 17. Nf3 b4 $36 18. Na4 Nd3 $13) 16... h6 17. Nf3 e5 (17... Qc7 $5)
18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. fxe5 Qxe5 $17 {0-1 (32) Gyimesi,Z (2395)-Ibragimov,I (2540)
Budapest 1993} *

