[SourceQuality "2"]

1. d4 d5
2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. a4 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. Rd1
{This is a more flexible move than 9.Nc3. The main point is that white intends
to take on c5 and develop the bishop to b2. In such cases the white knight is
better off on d2 than on c3} Be7 10. dxc5 {White intends to put the bishop on
b2, so it makes sense to open up the diagonal with gain of tempo once the
bishop has moved to e7} (10. Nc3 {- transposes to 9.Nc3}) ({White can also try
to maintain the tension, but this will likely transpose to the game while
allowing Black some interesting possibilities along the way} 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2
b6 12. Nbd2 Bb7 13. Rac1 Rfd8 14. dxc5 bxc5 $5 $13 {[%csl Ga5,Rb3,Gb4][%cal
Ga8b8,Gb8b3] this move is not normally available to Black and in this case
deserves serious consideration. White's queenside weaknesses are exposed and
a powerful outpost on b4 is created} (14... Bxc5 {transposes to the mianline}))
10... Bxc5 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 b6 13. Nbd2 ({Black does not need to fear the
doubling of his pawns. White's dark/squared bishop is such an important piece
that is amply compensated the weakening of the structure. For example, after} 
13. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Rac1 Bb7 (15... Ne5 $2 16. Bd5 $1 $18 {
1-0 (40) Guo,Q (2435)-Galliamova,A (2459) Astana 2013}) 16. Ne4 Rfd8 17. Bd3
Qb8 18. Ng3 Nb4 19. Bb1 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Qf8 21. Be4 (21. Nh5 Nd5 $11) (21. Nd4
Rd8 22. Qh5 Qg7 $11) 21... Bxe4 (21... Nd5 22. Nd4 Rc8 23. Qh5) 22. Nxe4 Rd8
$11) 13... Bb7 14. Rac1 {This is an important position in the variation. Black
will relocate the queen to e7 and trade off as many rooks as possible along
the d-file. Once this is done, he may start putting pressure on White's
queenside with moves like ...Nb4. However, I would not rush to put the knight
on b4 as this will surrender control over e5 (as seen in Anand-Ponomariov),
but most importantly it will deprive us of the key defensive manoeuvre...
Qe7 followed by ...Ba3} Rfd8 (14... Nb4 $6 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb2h8]} 15. Ng5 Qe7
16. Ndf3 h6 17. Nh3 Rfd8 18. Nf4 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Ne5 $14
{1-0 (46) Anand,V (2755)-Ponomariov,R (2743) Mainz 2002}) (14... Qe7 $5 {
[%cal Gc5a3,Gf8d8]}) 15. Bd3 ({Black should constantly be on the lookout for
this pivoting manoeuvre. The white knight is coming to e4 and the queen will
swing over to the kingside. Such positions can give White a powerful initiative
} 15. Ng5 $5 Qe7 $1 {this is a key part of Black's setup and the main way we
will neutralize White's kingside ambitions. In part, this is due to the
additional support we provide for the knight on f6, but mainly thanks to the
idea of trading off dark/squared bishops with ...Ba3. Therefore, it should not
be delayed any longer} 16. Bd3 (16. Nge4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Ba3 $11) 16... h6 17.
Nge4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Ba3 $11) 15... Qe7 16. h3 (16. Nc4 {White has prevented us
from trading off the dark-squared bishops, but now he will not be able to put
the knight on e4. In such cases, White will find it difficult to develop a
kingside attack.} a5 (16... Nb4 $5 17. Bb1 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rd8 $11) 17. Ng5 h6
18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Rd8 {1/2-1/2 (41) Hu,B (2264)-Reshef,O 
(2476) New York USA 2019}) 16... h6 (16... Ba3 $6 17. Bxa3 Qxa3 18. Nc4 Qb4 19.
e4 $36 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 17. Ne4 (17. e4 $2 Nh5 $15 {[%cal Gh5f4]}) (17. Nc4 Nb4
18. Bb1 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Peralta,F (2556)-Illescas Cordoba,
M (2605) Barcelona 2018}) 17... Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Rac8 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Ba1 ({
White should not get greedy with} 20. Bxc6 $6 Bxc6 21. Qxa6 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Qg5+
23. Kf1 Qf5 24. Kg2 Rd2 $44 (24... Qg5+ $11)) 20... Nb4 21. Qb2 f6 22. Bxb7
Qxb7 $11 {Black has been forced to slightly weaken his kingside, but control
over the d-file and White's tender queenside offset this minor problem.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Nc3 & 8...Bb4"]
[Black "9.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D24"]
[Annotator "GM Robert Hungaski"]
[PlyCount "44"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2004.04.22"]
[SourceQuality "2"]

1. d4 d5
2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 $5 {I have long believed this to be one of
White's most underrated (and dangerous) options against the QGA. The position
resembles that of the Tolush Gambit against the Slav (1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3
Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 b5), where Black can run into a lot of trouble is he
desperately tries to cling to his extra pawn. Black's most effective strategy
seems to be to return the material and secure some positional trumps instead.
Mainly, the d5-square. Therefore, Black should continue} a6 5. e4 (5. a4 $6 {
I'm surprised at how many times I have faced this move. I think Black is
already considerably better after} Nc6 $1 {Now that White has weakened his
queenside, the knight is heading for the a5-square should White play e2-e3 or
put pressure on d4 should White play e2-e4.} 6. e4 (6. e3 $6 Na5 7. Ne5 Be6 8.
Be2 c5 $17 {Now Black can undouble his pawns at will and easily defend the c4/
pawn by means of ...Qc7 and ...Rc8. Moreover, the bishop will now be developed
via g7: 0-1 (34) Teychene, J (2152)-Karpatchev, A (2421) Toulon 2001}) 6... Bg4
7. Be3 (7. d5 Ne5 8. Qd4 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 Bxf3 10. Rg1 e5 $1 $15 {0-1 (29)
Santiago, Y (2477)-Hungaski, R (2504) Buenos Aires 2017}) 7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 Na5
$1 {After this move I don't see a way for White to recover the pawn} 9. Qc2 e6
10. Rg1 c6 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. f4 g6 13. Bh3 Rd8 14. Rg3 b5 15. d5 exd5 16. Bd4 Bg7
17. axb5 axb5 18. exd5 O-O $17 {0-1 (32) Trichkov,V (2314)-Cernousek,L (2450)
Czech Republic 2017}) (5. e3 e6 6. Bxc4 b5 {[%csl Rc3] transposes to our main
line where White has prematurely developed the knight to c3. Therefore, all
the critical lines based on the a2-a4 pawn break will be much weaker}) 5... b5
6. e5 Nd5 7. a4 e6 (7... Bb7 $6 8. e6 $36) (7... c6 $6 8. axb5 Nxc3 9. bxc3
cxb5 10. Ng5 $36) 8. axb5 {Black has committed to give back the pawn, but he
has two different ways of doing this:} {After reviewing the lines and games
mentioned below, I came to appreciate why Delchev (in his excellent book
"Understanding the Queen's Gambit Accepted", 2005) recommends} Bb4 $1 {The
idea of this move is to force White to defend the knight on c3 and thanks to
this prevent the queen sortie to the kingside. If the bishop must go to d2,
then Kramnik's manoeuvre Be3, Nd2 and Qg4 will no longer be possible} (8... Nb6
$6 {The problem with this move is that Black is not able to create enough
pressure on the queenside to prevent White from launching an attack on the
other flank.} 9. Be3 $1 (9. Be2 Bb7 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O Be7 13.
Be3 O-O 14. Nd2 Qa8 $132 {is another critical position, but it seems that
Black is holding on as shown in the game: 0-1 (95) Ikonnikov, V (2587)-Mannion,
S (2346) Port Erin 2006}) 9... axb5 (9... Bb4 $6 10. Nd2 {with the idea to
continue with Qg4} axb5 11. Rxa8 Nxa8 12. Qg4 $36 {1-0 (49) Kramnik,V (2765)
-Kortschnoj,V (2635) Budapest 1996}) (9... Bb7 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Nxa6 12.
Be2 Be7 13. Nd2 $14 {1-0 (64) Yevseev,D (2520)-Semcesen,D (2460) Lvov 2009})
10. Rxa8 Nxa8 11. Nxb5 Nb6 12. Be2 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Qc2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (31)
Markus,R (2609)-Stevic,H (2613) Bol 2014}) 9. Qd2 {The point of 4.Nc3 is
centered around the idea of quickly transfering the queen over to the kingside.
In such cases, White's initiative on the kingside should not be underestimated.
For a time it appeared that the move 8...Bb4 put an end to this idea but
after 9.Qd2!? White's idea once again comes to life. Nevertheless, Black
should be able to keep the balance with 12...c5!N. It's worth pointing out
that Black should not be over-reliant on the weakness of the d5-square since he
too has some serious structural weaknesses on the queenside.} Nb6 10. Be2 Bb7
11. bxa6 Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O O-O 14. Qf4 {This is the whole point of 9.
Qd2. The queen finds an original way of getting to the kingside} c5 $1 {
Immediately creating pressure on d4 and undoubling the pawns. Black should not
delay this move} (14... Be7 $6 15. Qg4 Kh8 16. Rd1 Nb4 17. Ne4 N4d5 18. Nfg5
$36 {1-0 (40) Cordes,H (2231)-Mannion,S (2335) Hersonissos 2017}) (14... f5 $6
15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Qg4 $36 {1-0 (43) Grandelius,N (2643)-Edouard,R (2648)
Grosseto Prugna 2016}) (14... f6 $6 15. Qg3 $36) 15. dxc5 (15. Nb5 Bxf3 $5 (
15... cxd4 16. Nbxd4 Qd5 17. Rd1 Qe4 $11) 16. Bxf3 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Bc5 18. Rd1
Nb4 {all the black pieces join the game and White's bishop pair only makes his
position symbolically better. Black is fine} 19. Nc6 (19. Nxe6 Qxd1+ 20. Bxd1
fxe6 $132) 19... Qc7 20. Nxb4 Bxb4 21. Be3 Bc5 $11) (15. Qg3 $6 cxd4 16. Bh6 g6
17. Bxf8 Bxf8 $17) (15. Qg4 $6 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 cxd4 17. Bh6 g6 18. Ne4 (18. Bxf8
Bxf8 $44) 18... Nd7 19. Bxf8 Bxf8 $44) 15... Nxc5 16. Be3 (16. Rd1 Qb8 17. Bxc4
Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Rc8 20. Ba2 Nbd7 21. Be3 Nxe5 $11 {Black is at
least equal}) (16. Qg3 Ne4 (16... Bxc3 17. Bh6 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qf6 19. Bg5 Qf5
20. Bh6 Qf6 $11) 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Rd1 Qc7 $13) 16... Qc7 (16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3
Nd3 18. Qg3 Qc7 19. Ne4 Nd7 20. Bd4 Bc5 21. Nxc5 N7xc5 $132 {the two knights
have nothing to fear from the bishops}) (16... Qb8 $5) 17. Nb5 Qb8 18. Qg3 Bxf3
19. gxf3 (19. Bxf3 $2 Nbd7 $17 {[%csl Rb5,Re5]}) (19. Qxf3 Qxe5 $15) 19... Ncd7
20. f4 Nd5 (20... Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gb6d5]}) 21. Bxc4 Nxe3 22. fxe3 Bc5 $44 {
[%csl Rb2,Re3,Rg1] White has won a pawn, but his king is exposed (exacerbated
by the presence of opposite colored bishops) and has several vulnerable pawns}
*

