1. d4
d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e4 b5 6. e5 Nd5 7. a4 e6 8. axb5 Bb4 9.
Bd2 {this is White's most natural response and the one Black is hoping for.
White's pieces now occupy passive positions and Black does not need to worry
about the possibility of a kingside attack} Nb6 10. Be2 O-O (10... Bb7 11. bxa6
Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O O-O {simply transposes}) 11. O-O Bb7 12. bxa6 Rxa6
13. Rxa6 Nxa6 14. Be3 c5 $1 {Once again we encounter this key pawn break. All
of Black's pieces are ideally placed to support it, so Black has solved all
his opening problems} 15. Nb5 ({If White tries to win Black's c-pawn, then
Black usually get substantial counterplay against either b2, e5 or both pawns.
For example,} 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Qxd8 ({Delaying the exchange with} 16. Qd2 {
does not change the character of the position.} Bxf3 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. gxf3 (
18. Bxf3 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Nc5 $15) 18... Bxe3 19. fxe3 Nc5 $11 {Black enjoys 
pleasant equality.}) ({Keeping the queens on the board with} 16. Qc1 {allows
Black to fight for the initiative -} Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qc7 18. Bf4 (18. Nb5 Qxe5
$17) 18... Nb4 $132 {White should already be careful. Black is threatening ...
Nd3. In many lines, the e5-pawn would be vulnerable.}) 16... Rxd8 17. Rd1 Rxd1+
18. Nxd1 Nd7 19. Bxc4 Bxe3 20. Nxe3 Nc7 21. Nd2 Nxe5 $11) ({The move} 15. Qc1
$6 {is basically losing a pawn after} Bxf3 16. Bxf3 cxd4 17. Rd1 Bxc3 (17... d3
18. Ne4 $132) 18. bxc3 d3 $17) 15... Bd5 16. Nd6 {White's knight looks great
on d6, but Black can pivot around it quite easily} (16. Qc2 cxd4 17. Nfxd4 Nc5
$15) 16... f6 17. dxc5 (17. b3 $6 cxb3 $1 18. Bxa6 c4 $44 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4]}) (
17. Bd2 $2 cxd4 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. Qxd4 Nc6 20. Qe3 Nxe5 $17) 17... Bxc5 $1 $146
(17... Nxc5 $6 18. Nd2 (18. Qc2 $5) 18... fxe5 19. N6xc4 Nxc4 20. Nxc4 $14 {
1/2-1/2 (31) Barnaure,V (2433)-Rogozenco,D (2527) Predeal 2006}) 18. Nd2 (18.
Bxc5 Nxc5 19. Nd2 Nd3 20. N2xc4 (20. Bxd3 cxd3 $17) 20... Nf4 21. Ne3 fxe5 $15)
18... Bxe3 (18... Bxd6 19. exd6 Qxd6 20. Bxb6 Qxb6 21. Nxc4 Qc5 22. Ne3 Nb4 23.
Qd2 $14) 19. fxe3 Nc5 20. N2xc4 Nxc4 21. Nxc4 f5 $44 {[%csl Rb2,Re5] White is
up a pawn but has a terrible pawn structure. Black will have no problem
putting pressure on the e5 and b2 pawns} *

[Event "?"]
