 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4.
Qa4+ Nc6 5. Nc3 Nd5 $1 {This is the key idea behind the 4...Nc6 setup. The
knight is coming to b6, after which Black will prepare the ...e7-e5 pawn break.
} (5... Nd7 $6 {this move is usually interchangeable with ...Nd5. However, in
this case, there is one major difference:} 6. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd5b4]
now the black knight cannot go to b4, as in the main line}) 6. Qxc4 (6. e4 {
White's central expansion looks very tempting, but in fact, it only advances
Black's idea. For example, after} Nb6 7. Qd1 Bg4 {White's centre is anything
but stable, and it is unclear how White will retrieve his pawn} 8. d5 Ne5 9.
Bf4 Ng6 (9... Bxf3 $5 10. gxf3 Qd6 $15) 10. Bg3 e5 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Nd4 Bd6
$15 {1-0 (42) Sethuraman,S (2640)-Przybylski,W (2354) Berlin GER 2015}) ({
Another thematic move at White's disposal is} 6. Ne5 Nb6 7. Nxc6 Qd6 8. Qa5 {
[%csl Ga5]} (8. Qc2 bxc6 $5 $146 {Black takes on some serious structural
weaknesses for the sake of activity} (8... Qxc6 $11 {1-0 (60) Nakamura,H (2640)
-Sarkar,J (2380) Philadelphia 2006}) 9. e3 e5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Be2 Bc5 12. O-O
O-O 13. Bd2 Bf5 $15) 8... Qxc6 (8... bxc6 9. e3 $14 {now the pawn breaks on e5
and c5 are under control}) 9. e4 e6 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Bd7 12. Be2 (12. O-O-O
$6 {1-0 (32) Haik,A (2410)-Fico,M (2300) Cannes 1994} Na4 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc6b6]}
) 12... Qd6 $1 {[%cal Rd6d4,Rd6b4,Rc7c5] a multipurpose move that aside from
attacking d4 prepares both ...Qb4 as well as ...c5} 13. Bg3 (13. Rd1 Qb4 $15) (
13. a3 Qxd4 $17) 13... Qxd4 14. Bxc7 Qc5 15. Bxb6 Qxb6 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. Bxc4
Bd6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (32) Krasenkow,M (2636)-Donchenko,A (2501) Baku 2014}) 6...
Ndb4 $5 {[%csl Rc4] Black seizes the opportunity to take advantage of the poor
coordination between the queen on c4 and knight on c3. Now Black will be able
to develop at the expense of White's awkwardly placed queen} ({Black is
probably also fine after the more natural} 6... Nb6 7. Qb3 (7. Qd3 $6 e5 8.
Nxe5 (8. dxe5 Qxd3 9. exd3 Nb4 10. Kd2 Bf5 $44 {Black has more than enough
compensation for the sacrificing pawn.}) 8... Nb4 9. Qb1 Qxd4 10. Nf3 Qd6 11. e4
Bg4 12. a3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nc6 14. Nb5 Qe7 15. Be3 O-O-O $15 {With an advantage
for Black in 0-1 (32) Conquest,S (2260)-Dlugy,M (2460) New York,NY 1984}) 7...
e5 {again this thematical break looks interesting} 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Qc2 Nd4 10.
Qe4 Bc5 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. e3 Qxe4 13. Nxe4 Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Nxd2 O-O-O
$44 {With an unclear complications. The engine prefers White, but in a
practical game Black's initiative can be quite serious.}) 7. Qb3 Be6 8. Qa4 Bd7
9. Qd1 (9. Qb3 {is harmless} e5 (9... Be6 $11) 10. dxe5 Be6 11. Qa4 a6 12. Bd2
b5 13. Qd1 Nd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. e3 Qxe5 $36) 9... e5 $1 {whether the knight
goes to b6 or b4, black cannot do without this fundamental pawn break} 10. dxe5
(10. a3 {doesn't work due to} exd4 11. axb4 dxc3 12. bxc3 Qf6 $15) 10... Bf5
$44 {Black is not worried about the pawn deficit, since the pawn on e5 is weak
in every line and it is not clear how White will defend against the threats on
the queenside. For example, the game might continue} 11. Bg5 (11. e4 {is just
bad} Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 13. Bd2 Bg4 14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nxe5 $17 {Black
is close to winning}) 11... f6 $5 (11... Be7 12. e4 $1 (12. Bxe7 $6 Qxe7 13. e4
Rd8 $36 {The complications seems to be in Black's favour}) 12... Bg4 13. Bxe7
Qxe7 14. a3 Rd8 15. Qa4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 (16. axb4 $2 Qg5 $1 $19 {remember this
thematical resource!}) 16... Nd3+ 17. Bxd3 Rxd3 $13 {The reader can continue
analyzing this position. In a practical game Black's position looks quite
playable.}) (11... Nc2+ $2 {doesn't work} 12. Qxc2 $16) 12. exf6 (12. Qxd8+ $2
{is just losing} Rxd8 $19) (12. e4 $6 {is also not good} fxg5 13. exf5 g4 14.
Nd2 Nxe5 $15) 12... gxf6 13. e4 $8 (13. Bh4 $4 {is losing} Nc2+ $19) 13... fxg5
14. exf5 g4 15. Qe2+ (15. Nd2 Qe7+ $15) 15... Qe7 16. O-O-O Qxe2 17. Bxe2 gxf3
18. Bxf3 Bh6+ 19. Kb1 O-O 20. a3 Na6 (20... Ne5 $6 21. axb4 Nxf3 22. gxf3 Rxf5
23. Rd7 $14 {White has an advantage}) 21. g4 Nc5 $13 {a very messy position
arises where White can definite compensation for the piece. However, Black
should be fine as long as he is able to reincorporate the knight on a6 into
the game} *

