 1. d4 d5 2. c4
dxc4 3. e4 {Against the 3.e4 variation I believe Black's most effective plan
to be to force an overexpansion of White's centre in order to quickly chip
away at it. There are basically two ways of doing this: 3...Nc6, which forced
the d-pawn forward and 3...Nf6, which forces the e-pawn forward. Both moves
remind me of the underlying philosophy of the Alekhine Defense, with the major
difference that Black is not required to surrender so much space and so many
tempi. In the end, I decided for 3...Nf6 because it gives Black more
straight-forward play and excellent control over the centre thanks to the
powerful d5-outpost. However, though outside the scope of this database, 3...
Nc6 is a very legitimate line that I have essayed on numerous occasions.} Nf6
4. e5 (4. Nc3 {this sideline has long been established as good for Black.
However, it is quite popular at the club level. Black must strike immediately
with} e5 $1 5. Nf3 (5. d5 $2 {is bad} b5 $1 6. Nxb5 Nxe4 7. Bxc4 Bb4+ (7...
Nxf2 $5 {is also very interesting}) 8. Kf1 O-O (8... Nxf2 $5 {is possible here
as well}) 9. Qf3 Nd6 $17 {with an advantage for Black}) (5. dxe5 $6 Qxd1+ {
The endgame is in Black's favour} 6. Nxd1 (6. Kxd1 Ng4 7. Ke1 Bc5 8. Nh3 Nxe5
$17 {0-1 (19) Stojanovski,I (2258)-Stojanovic,M (2591) Struga 2011}) 6... Nxe4
7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. Nf3 (8. Bb5 Bb4+ 9. Ke2 Bd7 $17) 8... Bb4+ 9. Kf1 Be6 10. Bxe6
fxe6 $15 {White has managed to avoid material losses, but his coordination and
development remain poor}) (5. Be3 $6 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Bxd4 Be6 $15 {
it's not clear how White will regain his pawn}) 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 (6...
Bd6 $5 {this is an underrated option for Black} 7. Bxc4 O-O 8. Bg5 Nc6 9. Qe3
h6 10. Bh4 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qe2 c6 $15 {was already more comfortable for
Black in the game Timoshenko,G (2555)-Lekic,D (2370) Tivat 1995}) 7. Nxd4 Bc5
8. Ndb5 (8. Be3 Ng4 9. Nd5 (9. Bxc4 c6 $15) 9... Na6 (9... Nxe3 10. fxe3 Na6
11. Bxc4 c6 12. Bxa6 cxd5 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. O-O $132 {1/2-1/2 
(19) Knezevic,M (2500)-Garcia Palermo,C (2520) Havana 1985}) 10. Bxc4 c6 11.
Bxa6 cxd5 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ (13. Rd1 Rd8 14. exd5 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Nxe3 16.
fxe3 Bxe3 $15) 13... Kxd7 14. Rd1 (14. exd5 Rhe8 $17) (14. a3 Rhe8 $17) (14.
O-O Rhe8 $15) 14... Rhe8 15. Nf5 Nxe3 16. Nxe3 Rxe4 17. Rxd5+ Kc6 $15) 8... Na6
9. Bf4 c6 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Be6 {This is the critical position for the
line. White tried several moves, but Black's position seems to be better after
all of them.} 12. f3 (12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. Be2 Rhe8 14. f3 Nd7 15. Rd4 b5 16.
Rhd1 Nac5 $17 {0-1 (69) Aronian,L (2786)-Dominguez Perez,L (2719) Moscow 2009})
(12. e5 Nd7 13. Be2 f5 $5 14. O-O Nac5 15. Rad1 Kf7 16. f4 g6 17. Rd4 b5 $17 {
0-1 (34) Beliavsky,A (2650)-Ponomariov,R (2609) Enghien les Bains 1999}) 12...
O-O-O 13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Be2 f6 15. Rd2 Ndc5 (15... Nac5 16. Rhd1 b5 $17) 16. e5
f5 17. Rhd1 b5 $15 {0-1 (63) Korobov,A (2700)-Dominguez Perez,L (2732) Berlin
2015}) 4... Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Nc6 7. Ne2 (7. Be3 {has little independent
value} Bf5 8. Nf3 (8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Nb4 $5 10. O-O Be7 11. a3 N4d5 12. Rc1 Nxc3
13. Rxc3 Qd7 $11) (8. Ne2 e6 9. Nbc3 Qd7 {transposes}) (8. a3 e6 9. Nc3 Be7 10.
Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Qd7 12. Rc1 Rfd8 $11 {looks comfortable for Black} (12... Na5
$5) (12... Bg4 $5)) 8... e6 9. a3 Na5 10. Bc2 Bxc2 11. Qxc2 Qd5 $132 {Black
has excellent play along the light-squares}) 7... Bf5 (7... Bg4) 8. Nbc3 e6 9.
O-O (9. a3 Qd7 10. O-O O-O-O 11. Be3 {transposes}) 9... Qd7 (9... Be7 $5 {
[%cal Ge8g8] followed by 0-0 is also possible}) 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Qc1 {[%cal
Gf1d1,Gd4d5] This is the move proposed by Avrukh in "Grandmaster Repertoire -
The Queen's Gambit", 2016. The idea is to prepare the d5 pawn break as soon as
possible.} (11. Rc1 Kb8 {Since White is intending to play Na4, we might not
need to push our h-pawn since White will not have access to e4} (11... h5 12.
Na4 h4 13. h3 f6 14. Nxb6+ axb6 15. Ba4 Kb8 16. Bb5 fxe5 17. Qa4 $18 {/\Rxc6})
12. Na4 (12. Qd2 Nxe5 $17) 12... f6 13. Nc5 (13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Ba4 fxe5 15. Bb5
Qd5 16. Nc3 (16. Qa4 Nxd4 $19) 16... Qd6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. dxe5 Qxd1 19. Rfxd1
Be7 $17 {Espinosa Veloz,E (2516)-Quesada Perez,Y (2538) Santa Clara 2019})
13... Bxc5 14. dxc5 Nd5 (14... Qe7 $5 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Nd4 (16. Qe1 Nd5 $15 {
the white queen is much more passive compared to the game continuation}) 16...
Nxd4 17. cxb6 c5 $1 18. bxa7+ Ka8 $13) 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Ba4 (16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17.
Qxd5 Rxd5 18. Nf4 Rd7 19. Nh5 Rf8 20. f3 Bg6 21. Ng3 Rfd8 $15) 16... Qg7 17.
Qb3 Na5 18. Qa3 Nxe3 $6 (18... h5 $5 $40) 19. Qxe3 Rd3 20. Qf4 Rhd8 {1/2-1/2 
(73) Aleksandrov,A (2577)-Le,Q (2708) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019} 21. Rfd1 $13) (11.
a3 h5 $5 {Black would like to break with ...f7-f6 right away, but this runs
into the Ng3-e4 maneuver. Therefore, Black's idea is to take control over the
g3-square first and only then break on f6} (11... f6 $6 {is premature} 12. exf6
gxf6 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Qf3 (14. Qe2 $5 Kb8 15. Rfd1 Ne7 16. Nge4 Ned5 17. Rac1
Rg8 18. Nc5 $14) 14... Be7 15. Rad1 (15. Nge2 $5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge2f4]})
15... Na5 16. Ba2 Bc2 17. Rc1 (17. Rd2 Bb3 18. Bxb3 Nxb3 19. Rdd1 Nd5) 17...
Bb3 18. Bb1 f5 19. d5 $36 {Shabalov,A (2585)-Kaidanov,G (2577) /Saint Louis
2010}) 12. Rc1 (12. Bc2 h4 {Black is proceeding with his plan} 13. h3 Be7 14.
b4 g5 15. Be4 Kb8 16. f3 (16. Rc1 g4 $40) 16... f6 $13) (12. Qc1 h4 13. Rd1 (
13. h3 Kb8 {is a lot like the main line}) 13... Qe8 (13... h3 $5 {is possible
too}) 14. Bc2 Bxc2 15. Qxc2 f6 16. exf6 gxf6 17. h3 Kb8 18. b4 Bd6 19. Kh1 Qf7
20. Rac1 Rhg8 $15 {Black has a better game in Izoria,Z (2450)-Ganguly,S (2498),
Yerevan 2000}) (12. Ng3 {is just bad for White} Bg6 13. Nge4 h4 14. h3 Nxd4 $17
) (12. Ba2 {doesn't make so much sense} h4 13. b4 (13. h3 f6 14. exf6 (14. b4
Kb8 15. Qc1 Qe8 16. f4 Qg6 17. Kh1) 14... gxf6 15. Nf4 Bh6 $17) 13... f6 (13...
h3 $5 14. g3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qc6 $19) 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Nf4 Bh6 16. d5 Bxf4 17.
Bxf4 exd5 18. Rc1 Ne5 19. Qd4 Bh3 20. f3 Rhg8 21. Rc2 Qf5 22. Re2 {
Kasimdzhanov,R (2603)-Jonkman,H (2421) Wijk aan Zee 1999} Bxg2 $1 23. Rxg2
Rxg2+ 24. Kxg2 Rg8+ 25. Kh1 (25. Kf2 Nd3+ 26. Ke3 Nxf4 27. Qxf4 Re8+ $19) 25...
Qh3 26. Rf2 Nxf3 $19) 12... h4 13. h3 f6 14. Na4 (14. exf6 $6 {this capture
usually leads to trouble for White} gxf6 15. d5 (15. Nf4 Bh6 16. d5 Qg7 $17)
15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 $17) 14... Nd5 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Rxc5 {Van Hoolandt,P 
(2245)-Annoni,R (2076) Imperia 2007} Nxe3 17. fxe3 fxe5 18. Ba4 Qd6 19. b4 (19.
Bxc6 Qxc5 $17) 19... Ne7 20. Rxe5 Qxe5 21. dxe5 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Nd5 $11) 11...
Kb8 (11... f6 {is again premature} 12. Rd1 $1 (12. exf6 $6 {as we'll see,
White should refrain from releasing the tension in this way} gxf6 13. Ng3 Bg6
14. Rd1 Nd5 (14... Ne7 15. d5 $1 $16) 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Ba4 h5 $132) 12... Nb4
13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Nge4 N4d5 15. f3 (15. a4 $5) 15... Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Nd5 17. Qf2
$14 {1-0 (74) Borisova,E (2292)-Badelka,O (2383) Sochi 2019}) (11... h5 $6 {
is not working well here due to} 12. Rd1 h4 13. d5 $16) ({Originally I was
going to recommend this line for Black, but as I was finishing this database my
friend IM David Vigorito showed me that Black was actually struggling after} 
11... Nb4 $6 12. Rd1 Kb8 (12... Be7 $6 13. d5 $1 $16) (12... h5 $6 13. d5 $1
$16 {is devastating, again}) 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Nge4 {Since the d4-d5 pawn break
has been taken under control, White aims for his other asset in the position:
the c5-square. As long as the white queen is on c1, instead of a rook, Black
has nothing to worry about. But he must not delay since White will soon play
Qd2 followed by Rac1 and the black queen will not find a comfortable square} h6
(14... Qc6 15. f3 {[%cal Ge3g5,Gc1d2,Ga1c1]} Be7 16. Bf2 h5 17. Qd2 h4 18. Rac1
$14 {this is exactly the kind of position white is aiming for. Black lacks
counterplay and White will slowly but surely start expanding on the queenside})
(14... Qe8 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Nc5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nc2 18. Bxc2 Bxc2 19. Rd2 Bg6 20.
b3 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4] 1-0 (45) Kotanjian,T (2481)-Egin,V (2340) Tashkent 2018})
(14... N4d5 15. Bg5 Re8 16. Nc5 Qc8 17. a4 $36 {1-0 (57) Kotanjian,T (2466)
-Savitskiy,S (2415) Moscow 2018}) 15. f3 Be7 16. Bf2 N4d5 17. Qd2 $14 {Black
is starting to run out of useful moves}) (11... Qe8 12. Rd1 h5 13. Ng3 Bg6 14.
Nge4 h4 15. h3 Bf5 16. f3 Kb8 17. a3 {since White does not have Qf4 black can
actually take the time to play} Be7 18. Bf2 f6) 12. Rd1 Qe8 $5 {This is an
interesting way of turning the tables on White who now runs the risk of having
his own queen misplaced. Black's idea is to push the h-pawn as far as possible
(usually h4) and then follow with...f6 (sometimes ...Be7 won't even be
necessary!) and ...Qg6 usually with good play on the kingside} 13. Ng3 (13. h3
h5 14. Ng3 Bg6 15. Nge2 (15. Nge4 h4) 15... h4 {1/2-1/2 (53) Glembek,B (2231)
-Davidov,D (2166) ICCF email 2015} (15... Bf5) 16. Na4 f6 $5 (16... Nd5 17.
Nac3 Nb6 {1/2-1/2 (53) Glembek,B (2231)-Davidov,D (2166) ICCF email 2015}) 17.
Nf4 (17. Nxb6 axb6 18. Ba4 Be4 19. Nc3 Bf5 20. a3 fxe5 (20... Qg6) 21. dxe5
Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1 Be7 $13) 17... Bf5) ({Avrukh recommends} 13. a3 {but I think
this is too slow considering how direct Black's idea is} h5 14. Bc2 Bxc2 15.
Qxc2 f6 $1 (15... a6 $6 16. b4 h4 17. h3 Rg8 18. b5 axb5 19. Nxb5 $16) 16. Nf4
g5 $132 {0-1 (40) Cruz,C (2571)-Studer,N (2484) Batumi 2018}) 13... Bg6 14.
Nge4 h5 (14... Be7 $6 {is too slow here. Black can often do without this move,
so he should wait for an see if it is actually necessary} 15. f3 h5 16. Bf2 h4 17.
h3 Bf5 18. Qf4 $1 {solves the problem of where the white queen should go,
while taking the sting out of ...f6} g5 (18... f6 19. exf6 gxf6 20. d5 $16) 19.
Qe3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Rawlings,A (2346)-Volodarsky,Y (2343) ICCF email 2016} (
19. Nxg5 Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Bxh3 $17)) (14... Bf5 {will probably transpose to 14...
h5}) 15. f3 (15. Bg5 $2 {is bad because of} Rxd4 $17) (15. Nc5 {is without a
threat and Black can continue with his plan} h4 16. h3 Bf5 17. N3a4 f6 $132)
15... h4 16. h3 (16. Bf2 $5 h3 17. g3 Na5 {looks good for Black too}) 16... Bf5
{[%cal Ge8g6,Gf7f6] An important move that prepared the immediate
incorporation of the black queen to the kingside via the g6-square} (16... Na5
$5 {this move would be great if it forced the white bishop to c2} 17. Bf2 $1 {
when the white queen is ready to come to f4 it is time for Black to make a
change of plans} (17. Bc2 $6 Bf5 18. Bf2 f6 $1 19. exf6 gxf6 20. Nxf6 Qg6 {
and compared to the main line White does not have enough time to put the
knight on g4} 21. Bxf5 exf5 $19 {[%csl Rf6]}) 17... Nxb3 18. axb3 Bxe4 (18...
Bf5 19. Qf4 $14) 19. fxe4 (19. Nxe4 Nd5 20. Nc5 Qb5 $15) 19... f6 $13) 17. Bf2
$1 {It's important for White to get this bishop out of the way as soon as
possible so that the white queen can find a better square} (17. a3 f6 $5 ({
since white does not have Qf4 black can actually take the time to play} 17...
Be7 $13 {[%cal Gf7f6]}) 18. exf6 Qg6 19. Ng5 (19. fxg7 Bxg7 $17) (19. Kh1 gxf6
20. Bf2 Bh6 $19) (19. f7 Qxf7 20. Ne2 Be7 21. Ng5 Qf6 22. Ne4 Qf7 $11) (19. d5
exd5 20. Bxd5 Bxh3 21. Qc2 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Bf5 $13) 19... Qxf6 20. d5 (20. Nge4
Qg6 21. Kh1 Be7 $13) (20. Kh1 Nd5 21. Nge4 Qg6 22. Bg1 Be7 $13) 20... exd5 21.
Nxd5 Qg6 22. Bf4 Bd6 $11) 17... f6 $1 {A powerful pawn sacrifice that breathes
life into black's position. The idea is to bring the queen to g6 as well as to
open the g-file and the a1-h8 and the c1-h6 diagonals for black's dark-squared
bishop} (17... Be7 18. Qf4 $1 {solves the problem of where the white queen
should go, while taking the sting out of ...f6} g5 (18... f6 19. exf6 gxf6 20.
d5 $16) 19. Qe3 $14) 18. exf6 (18. Qf4 Qg6) 18... Nd5 $1 19. Ba4 {I briefly
analyzed the other options for White too.} (19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Nc3 Qg6 $44) (19.
fxg7 Bxg7 $44) (19. Qd2 Qg6 20. Qg5 Bxe4 21. Nxe4 Qf7 22. fxg7 Bxg7 $44) (19.
Be3 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 gxf6 21. Nxf6 Qg6 22. Ng4 Bg7 $44) (19. Kh1 gxf6 20. Nxd5
exd5 21. Nxf6 Qf7 (21... Qg6 22. Nxd5 $16) 22. Qg5 (22. Ng4 $2 Bxg4 23. hxg4 h3
$17) 22... Be6 23. Ng4 Bxg4 24. Qxg4 (24. hxg4 h3 $40) 24... Rg8 $44) 19...
gxf6 20. Nxd5 (20. Bxc6 Qg6 $3 {amazing resource!} 21. Kh1 (21. Bb5 $2 Bh6 22.
Qc2 Bxh3 23. Bf1 Rdg8 $19) 21... Bxh3 (21... Bh6 22. Qb1 Rdg8 23. Rg1) 22. Rg1
(22. gxh3 Qf5 $19) 22... Bf5 23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Nc5 Bd6 $40) (20. Kh1 $6 Bh6 21.
Qc2 Ncb4 22. Qb3 Qg6 $17) 20... exd5 21. Nxf6 Qg6 22. Ng4 Nb4 $44 {The knight
on g4 is White's saving grace. However, Black retains an active position that
compensates the pawn deficit.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
