[SourceQuality "2"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 {This is the first major
crossroads of the variation. The issue that will define the outcome of the
opening is whether Black will be able to create real pressure on White's
backward pawn on d4. If not, then Black's position will remain passive due to
a lack of space and pawn breaks. White can now retreat either to b3 or d3. The
former is by far the most common retreat, while the latter aims to make it
hard for Black to develop his light-squared bishop.} 6. Bb3 Nc6 (6... Bf5 $5 {
is an interesting way of avoiding the line that leads to a draw by perpetual
check, although this allows White to develop the knight to the more active
f3-square without having to fear the pin. If Black wants to play with the
bishop on f5, then this is the move-order he should use} 7. Nc3 (7. e6 Bxe6 8.
Bxe6 fxe6 $13 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]}) (7. Qf3 e6 8. Qxb7 Qxd4 $132) (7. d5 c6 8.
Nc3 cxd5 9. Nxd5 e6 $11) 7... e6 8. Nf3 $1 (8. Nge2) 8... Nc6 9. O-O Be7 (9...
Qd7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd4d5] followed by Rfd1 and d5
looks very dangerous for Black. As a general rule, it's not a good idea to
castle queenside when the White knight has been developed to f3}) 10. a3 O-O
11. Be3 Qd7 12. Qe2 a5 13. Rfd1 a4 14. Ba2 Nd5 15. Rac1 Na5 $13) 7. Nf3 $5 {
Before it was considered that allowing the bishop to g4 created discomfort for
White's d4-pawn. In fact, in order to avoid getting the worse position White
would have to take a quick draw by perpetual check. However, matters are no so
simple. White can definitely play with the knight on f3 and allow the pin} Bg4
(7... Bf5 $6 {This is not the right way of going for ...Bf5} 8. d5 $1 Nb4 (8...
Bxb1 9. Rxb1 Na5 10. Ba4+ c6 11. b4 Nac4 12. dxc6 Qxd1+ 13. Bxd1 bxc6 14. e6 f6
15. a4 Nd5 16. Be2 $16) (8... Na5 9. Nc3 Nxb3 10. Qxb3 Bd3 11. e6 f6 12. Be3
Bc4 13. Qb4 a5 14. Qc5 Qd6 15. Qxd6 exd6 16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. b3 $16 {1-0 (53)
Kouatly,B (2460)-Semkov,S (2410)/Bulgaria 1985/MCL}) 9. Nc3 Nd3+ 10. Kf1 Nc5 (
10... e6 11. Nd4 Bg6 12. h4 $16) 11. Be3 $16) 8. Be3 ({There is a nice draw by
perpetual check after} 8. Ng5 Bxd1 9. Bxf7+ Kd7 10. Be6+ Ke8 11. Bf7+ $11) ({
Another way White can try to capitalize on the unprotected bishop on g4 is with
} 8. Bxf7+ $5 Kxf7 9. Ng5+ Ke8 10. Qxg4 Qxd4 11. Qe2 Qxe5 12. Be3 Nd5 13. Nf3
Qf5 14. O-O e6 15. Nc3 Rd8 16. Rfe1 $44 ({GM Moskalenko tried} 16. Nb5 Bd6 17.
Rae1 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Rf8 19. e4 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 a6 $15 {0-1 (35) Moskalenko,V (2525)
-Borges Mateos,J (2500)/Belgorod 1990/EXT 1999}) 16... Be7 17. Bd2 (17. Nb5 a6
(17... Nxe3 $2 18. fxe3 a6 19. Nxc7+ Kd7 20. Nxa6 $1 $16 {1-0 (33) Jussupow,A 
(2590)-Portisch,L (2635)/Tunis 1985/IZT}) 18. Nbd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Qe4 $15) 17...
Nxc3 18. Bxc3 (18. bxc3 Rd6 19. Rab1 b6 20. Rb5 Qd3 21. Qxd3 Rxd3 22. Rxe6 Kd7
$15 {1/2-1/2 (54) Seirawan,Y (2595)-Speelman,J (2625)/ Saint John 1988/
Candidates}) 18... Kf7 19. Qc4 Bf6 20. Re3 Rhe8 (20... Bxc3 $2 21. Ng5+ $1 Kg6
22. Qxc3 $36 {1-0 (33) Alburt,L (2515)-Gulko,B (2505)/Somerset 1986/EXT 2000})
21. Rae1 Qd5 22. Qg4 e5 $13) 8... e6 9. O-O Be7 ({Now the idea of castling
queenside is not so appealing} 9... Qd7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Qe2 f6 12. Rfd1 Kb8
13. exf6 gxf6 14. h3 Bh5 15. d5 $16) 10. Nc3 O-O 11. h3 Bh5 {The critical
position for this line} (11... Bxf3 $6 {is playable, but probably White is
slightly better} 12. Qxf3 Nxd4 13. Qxb7 Rb8 14. Qe4 Nxb3 (14... c5 $1 {is
probably the best try for Black} 15. Rfd1 Nd7 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Qxd4 Nc5 $44) (
14... Nf5 15. Rfd1 Qc8 16. Rac1 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Rd8 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Ne4 $13)
15. axb3 Nd7 16. Rfd1 Qc8 17. Rxa7 $16 Rxb3 $2 18. Qa4 $18) 12. Rc1 (12. d5 {
looks tempting, but Black should be OK after} exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxe5 14. g4 Nxf3+
15. Qxf3 Bg6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qxb7 Be4 18. Qa6 Qf6 $36) (12. g4 {doesn't
lead to an advantage after} Bg6 13. Qe2 Na5 14. Bc2 Qd7 15. Rfd1 Rad8 16. Rac1
Nac4 (16... Nd5) 17. Be4 Nxe3 18. fxe3 c6 19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. Ne4 f5 $132) (12.
a3 {looks too slow} Bxf3 (12... Na5 $5 13. Ba2 Nac4 14. Qe2 Nxe3 15. fxe3 c5
$13) 13. Qxf3 (13. gxf3 {is not losing a pawn, but Black has enough
counterplay after Qd7 followed by Rd8}) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 (14. Qxb7 Nxb3 $19)
14... Qxd4 15. Qxb7 Qxe5 $15) 12... Bxf3 (12... Rb8 $5 {preparing to take on
f3 and d4, without leaving the b7-pawn unprotected} 13. a3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Na5
$132) (12... Qd7 13. g4 Bg6 14. d5 $16) (12... Nb4 13. a3 N4d5 14. Ne4 Bg6 15.
Nc5 Rb8 16. Qe2 h6 17. Rfd1 c6 $14 {White is slightly better, but Black is
rock-solid}) 13. Qxf3 Nxd4 14. Qxb7 Nxb3 15. axb3 Qc8 16. Qc6 (16. Qe4 a5 $132)
16... a5 17. Nb5 Nd5 $132 {with a complex position where Black's chances seem
to be at least equal} *

