1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 6. Bd3 $5 {This bishop
retreat should not be underestimated. White's idea is to prevent the natural
development of our light-squared bishop. However, the obvious drawback is that
it does not control the d5-square} Nc6 7. Be3 Nb4 {This is the most direct way
of punishing White's bishop retreat to d3} (7... Be6 {is playable, but White
is better after:} 8. Ne2 (8. Nf3 Qd7 9. O-O O-O-O 10. Nc3 Bg4 $132) 8... Qd7 9.
Nbc3 O-O-O 10. O-O $14 {leads to a surprisingly difficult position for Black
where it is not easy to solve the problem of the light-squared bishop without
giving up control over the d5-square}) 8. Be4 f5 (8... N4d5 $5 9. Nc3 c6 $14 {
is a solid alternative, but distinct from the types of positions we are aiming
for and thus outside the scope this repertoire}) 9. exf6 (9. Bf3 $6 f4 $1 10.
Bxf4 Bf5 (10... Qxd4 $5) 11. Ne2 (11. Na3 $2 Nd3+ $19) 11... Nc2+ 12. Kf1 Nxa1
$17) (9. a3 $5 {Kramnik's choice} N4d5 (9... fxe4 $6 10. axb4 e6 11. Qh5+ (11.
Nc3 Nd5 $132) 11... g6 12. Qh3 Bxb4+ 13. Nc3 $14 {looks very good for White})
10. Bf3 {this retreat looks the most sensible one} (10. Bc2 e6 11. Nf3 Be7 12.
Nc3 O-O 13. Qd3 Bd7 14. h4 Bc6 $15) (10. Bd3 e6 11. Nh3 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Qh4+ 13.
Nf2 Qg5 (13... Qh6 $5) 14. Qf3 Nd5 15. Ke2 Bd7 $15 {0-1 (40) Le Ruyet,L (2282)
-Karpatchev,A (2508) Anogia 2017}) (10. Bxd5 {White scores well with this move,
but I don't buy it. The light squares look too good} Nxd5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3
Qd5 13. Nf3 Qc4 14. Qc2 (14. Nd2 Qc6 $13) 14... e6 15. Nd2 Qc6 16. O-O b6 17.
f3 Be7 $15 {is better for Black according to Edouard}) 10... Bd7 $1 {Black
should not delay the transfer of the bishop to c6. Otherwise, it might never
get there} 11. Nh3 (11. Qc2 e6 12. Ne2 Bc6 13. Nd2 Be7 (13... g5 $5 14. Bh5+
Kd7 $15) 14. Nb3 O-O 15. O-O g5 16. h3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Nd5 18. Qd2 Bb5 19. e4 g4
20. exd5 gxf3 21. Rxf3 Bxe2 22. Qxe2 Qxd5 $15 {1-0 (55) Davtyan,A (1942)
-Kirillov,D (2275) Moscow 2019}) 11... Bc6 12. Nc3 (12. Ng5 Qc8 13. e6 g6 14.
Qe2 Bg7 $15) 12... e6 13. O-O Qd7 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Qh5+ g6 17. Qh6
O-O-O $15 {0-1 (38) Navara,D (2737)-Caruana,F (2807) Saint Louis 2017}) 9...
exf6 10. Nc3 (10. a3 f5 $1 {Again this well-known idea saves the day} (10...
N4d5 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Bxg6+ hxg6 13. Qxh8 Bf5 14. Nc3 Qd7 15. Nge2 O-O-O 16. O-O
g5 $44 {[%csl Rh8]}) 11. axb4 fxe4 12. Nc3 (12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qe5+ Kf7 14. Nc3 (
14. Qxh8 $2 Bxb4+ $19) 14... Bxb4 $15) 12... Be6 13. Nh3 (13. Qh5+ Bf7 14. Qg4
Nd5 15. Qxe4+ Qe7 16. Qxe7+ Bxe7 17. b5 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Bc4 $15) 13... Bd6 14.
Ng5 (14. O-O O-O 15. Ng5 Bc4 16. Re1 Bxb4 17. Qh5 h6 18. Ngxe4 Qd7 $11 {
looks fine for Black}) 14... Bc4 15. Ngxe4 (15. Qg4 Qe7 16. Nxh7 Bxb4) 15...
O-O 16. b3 Bd5 $44 {and even thought Black was down a pawn he was certainly
not worse in the game 0-1 (41) Ibragimov,I (2610)-Yakovich,Y (2560) St
Petersburg 1998}) (10. Qh5+ $2 {is not working, because of} g6 11. Bxg6+ hxg6
12. Qxh8 Nc2+ $19) 10... f5 $1 (10... c6 $6 11. a3 N4d5 12. Qh5+ $16) (10...
Be6 $6 11. Bxb7 $16) 11. Bb1 {This is one of the critical positions of the
variation. Black enjoys good control over the d5-square, but in order to
achieve this, he had to push the pawn all the way to f5. This has weakened the
e5-square, and if White manages to place a knight there, then he will be
better. Black's main strategy here is to take the bishop on e3 and put
pressure on White's backward pawn} (11. Bf3 {it turns out the bishop is not so
well-placed here. Back will eventually put a pawn on c6 and its scope will be
severely restricted. In the meantime, Black will carry out the same idea of
capturing the bishop on e3} N4d5 12. Bd2 {White should not allow his bishop to
get traded without a fight} (12. Nh3 $6 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bd6 (13... Qh4+ 14. Nf2
Bd6 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Nxd6 cxd6 17. O-O Qe7 18. Qd3 Be6 19. b3 Bd5 20. e4 fxe4
21. Nxe4 Rae8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Huebner,R (2603)-Koneru,H (2603) Marianske
Lazne 2009}) 14. O-O O-O 15. g3 (15. Nf4 c6 16. Qb3+ Kh8 17. Nd3 Qg5 $15) 15...
c6 16. Nf4 Qe7 17. Qd3 (17. e4 {doesn't work well after:} Bxf4 18. gxf4 fxe4
19. Bxe4 Bf5 $17) 17... Bd7 18. Rae1 Rae8 $15 {Black's chances are preferable})
12... Be6 13. Nge2 Qd7 14. O-O O-O-O 15. Re1 Rg8 16. Bg5 Re8 17. Nf4 Nxf4 18.
Bxf4 g5 19. Be5 Bg7 20. Rc1 Bxe5 21. dxe5 Qxd1 22. Bxd1 a6 $15 {led to a
better endgame for Black in the game ½-½ (94) Karpov, A (2725)-Short, N (2685)
Linares 1992 Candidates}) 11... N4d5 (11... Bd6 $5 {with this move Black
intends to quickly develop the queenside and perhaps castle on that side of
the board} 12. Nf3 Be6 (12... N4d5 13. Bg5 Qd7 14. O-O O-O 15. Re1 c6 16. Ne5
Qc7 17. Bd3 $14) (12... O-O 13. O-O Be6 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Ne5 $14) 13. Ng5 (13.
O-O Qd7 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 O-O-O 16. Qxd7+ Rxd7 $15) 13... Qd7 14. Nxe6 Qxe6
15. O-O O-O (15... O-O-O $5) 16. a3 N4d5 17. Ba2 c6 18. Qf3 Kh8 19. Rfe1 Rae8
20. Rac1 Qd7 $11 {0-1 (79) Dragun,K (2523)-Semcesen,D (2431) Lublin 2013}) 12.
Nf3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bd6 (13... g6 $5 $146 {this is a new way of treating the
position, seeking to discourage the e3-e4 break due to the pressure on d4} 14.
e4 (14. O-O Bg7) 14... Bg7 15. O-O O-O 16. exf5 (16. e5 Be6 $15) 16... Bxf5 17.
Bxf5 Rxf5 $11) 14. e4 O-O {Maintaining the tension is an important resource at
Black's disposal since there is nothing to fear in the e4-e5 advance, given
how weak the hanging pawns would become} 15. O-O (15. e5 $6 Be7 $15 {[%csl Rd4,
Re5]}) 15... c6 16. a4 (16. Qb3+ {Black scored very well after this move in
the following high-rated games} Kh8 17. e5 Be7 18. a4 Nd5 (18... g5 $5 19. a5
g4 20. axb6 gxf3 21. Rxf3 Qxd4+ 22. Kh1 Qxe5 $17) 19. Ba2 Rb8 20. a5 Ne3 21.
Ne2 f4 22. Rf2 Ng4 23. Rff1 Ne3 24. Rf2 Ng4 25. Rff1 Ne3 {1/2-1/2 (25)
Mamedyarov,S (2764)-Ponomariov,R (2741) Tashkent 2012}) (16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5
Rxf5 18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Rae1 Qd7 20. Ne4 Raf8 $11 {0-1 (31) Ding,L (2702)
-Karjakin,S (2775) Beijing 2012}) (16. e5 $6 {is a positional mistake} Be7 $15)
16... fxe4 (16... a5 {is possible too}) 17. Bxe4 Kh8 18. a5 (18. Qc2 Bg4 19.
Rae1 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Qh4 21. g3 Qxd4+ $17 {0-1 (33) Jakovenko,D (2713)-Rublevsky,
S (2695) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013}) 18... Nd5 (18... Nd7 {looks better for White
after} 19. Qe1 $1 (19. a6 $2 Nf6 20. axb7 Bxb7 21. Bc2 c5 $15) 19... Nf6 20.
Bc2 $40 {[%cal Ge1h4]}) (18... Nc4 $5 {is also tempting} 19. Qd3 Be6 20. Bxh7
Rxf3 (20... Nxb2 21. Qe4 Bc4 22. Qg4 $40) 21. Rxf3 Qh4 $44 {with heavy
complications. The reader can continue the analysys here.}) 19. Bxd5 cxd5 20.
Ne5 (20. Nxd5 {is too greedy} Be6 (20... Bg4 21. Ne3 Bxf3 22. Rxf3 Qh4 23. Rh3
Qf2+ 24. Kh1 Rae8 $44) 21. Nc3 Bc7 $44) 20... Be6 21. Qh5 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Qxa5 (
22... Kg8 $11) 23. Ne4 Bxe5 24. Qxe5 Bg8 25. Nd6 Qb6 26. Rf6 Qxb2 27. h4 $44 {
1/2-1/2 (40) Tomashevsky,E (2720)-Romanov,E (2611) Eilat 2012} *

