1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ne2 $5 (7.
Nf3 $6 Bg4 $132) 7... Bg4 (7... Nb4 $6 {without a bishop on e3 this idea is
not so strong, since now Black will not be able to play the manoeuvre...
Nb4-d5-xe3} 8. Be4 f5 (8... c6 $5) 9. exf6 exf6 10. O-O $14) 8. f3 (8. Be3 {
gives Black enought time to transfer the bishop to g6} e6 (8... Qd7 9. Nbc3
O-O-O 10. O-O Nxe5 11. Bb5 Nc6 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rc1 $44 {1-0 (34) Moiseenko,A 
(2710)-Annaberdiev,M (2417) Kocaeli 2015}) 9. Nbc3 (9. a3 Bxe2 10. Bxe2 Qd7 11.
O-O O-O-O $132 {xd4}) 9... Nb4 10. Be4 c6 11. O-O Bh5 12. Qb3 Bg6 13. Nf4 (13.
a3 Bxe4 14. Nxe4 Qd5 15. Nd2 Qxb3 16. Nxb3 N4d5 $11 {0-1 (58) Martinovic,S 
(2527)-Varga,Z (2447) Meissen 2013}) 13... Bxe4 14. Nxe4 N4d5 15. Nd3 Be7 16.
Bd2 Nc7 $1 (16... O-O 17. Ndc5 $36) 17. Bb4 (17. Ndc5 Qd5 18. Qg3 Bxc5 19. Nxc5
O-O-O $13) 17... Qxd4 (17... Nb5 $5) 18. Bxe7 Qxe4 19. Bd6 $44 {White has some
compensation for the pawn, but not much more ½-½ (31) Lampert, J (2469)-Varga,
Z (2461) Budapest 2015}) 8... Be6 {This idea became popular after the game
Bukic-Petrosian. Black will use the d5-square as a pivot point for his minor
pieces. If Black opts for the ...Nb4-d5 manoeuvre, then his will usually
follow-up with ...f5. If the bishop goes to d5 instead, then usually Black
will follow-up with ...e6} (8... Bh5 {is playable, but White's position is
slightly better after} 9. Nbc3 $1 (9. e6 $5 $36 {the light-squared bishops
should keep a watchful eye on the e6-square in order to prevent such sacrifices
}) (9. Nf4 $2 {doesn't work, because of} Qxd4 $1 10. Nxh5 Qxe5+ $17) (9. Be3 e6
(9... Bg6 10. e6 $1 $36) 10. Nf4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 $132) 9... e6 10. Be3 (10.
Be4 $1 {I can't find equality for Black after this move} Bg6 11. O-O Qd7 12.
Be3 O-O-O 13. Rc1 $14) 10... Be7 11. O-O Bg6 12. Be4 O-O 13. Bf2 Qd7 14. a3 $14
{Le Quang Liem (2664)-Fernandez, D (2351)/Ho Chi Minh City 2011}) 9. Nbc3 Qd7 (
9... Nb4 10. Be4 c6 $14 {once again is a pretty solid alternative for Black})
10. Ne4 {This is by far White's most common response. In order to understand
why this is, it's worth reviewing some lines where White continues with more
natural moves and how the inclusion of the f2-f3 advance actually makes
White's position more delicate} (10. Be3 Nb4 $1 {It's important for Black to
put a knight on d5 in order to capitalize on the weakened e3-square} (10...
O-O-O 11. Be4 (11. O-O Nxe5 12. Bb5 Nc6 13. Na4 Bd5 14. Rc1 e6 15. Nec3 $44) (
11. Rc1 Nxe5 12. Bb5 Nc6 13. Na4 Bd5 14. Nec3 $44) 11... Bd5 12. O-O e6 $13)
11. Nf4 (11. Be4 O-O-O 12. Nf4 (12. O-O f5 13. exf6 exf6 $15) 12... f5 $1 {
taking the crucial e4-square under control} 13. Nxe6 (13. a3 N4d5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5
15. O-O e6 $13) 13... Qxe6 14. Bb1 Qd7 15. a3 N4d5 16. Bf2 e6 17. O-O g5 $132)
11... Nxd3+ 12. Nxd3 (12. Qxd3 $6 O-O-O 13. O-O Bc4 $17) 12... Bd5 13. Nc5 Qc6
14. Rc1 e6 15. b3 (15. O-O Nc4 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Qe2 Bxc5 18. dxc5 Nxe3 19.
Qxe3 O-O-O $11) (15. Bf2 a5 16. O-O Be7 17. b3 O-O 18. Qe2 Rfc8 19. Rfd1 h6 20.
Rc2 Rab8 21. N3e4 Qe8 22. a4 Bc6 23. Rdc1 Nd5 $132) 15... Rd8 (15... Bxc5 16.
dxc5 Nc8 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. f4 Ne7 19. O-O Nf5 20. Bf2 h5 $13) 16. Qe2 Bxc5 17.
dxc5 Nc8 18. O-O O-O 19. b4 Ne7 20. Bg5 Rfe8 $13) (10. O-O $6 Nxd4 $15) 10...
Bd5 11. Nc5 Qc8 {This is the critical position of the variation. Black's main
problem is that he has too many pieces for too few squares. If he is able to
alleviate the problem of his lack of space, then his position will become
quite comfortable. Therefore, Black must be alert for the possibility of
trading pieces. These trades can take place on c5, c4 or b4} 12. a3 (12. Be3 e6
13. Nf4 Nb4 14. Be2 (14. Bb5+ c6 15. Be2 Bc4 $1 {this is a typical manoeuvre
when the White knight is on f4} 16. Nh5 N6d5 17. Bg5 h6 18. Bc1 Bxe2 19. Qxe2
g6 20. Ng3 b6 21. Nb3 a5 $15 {0-1 (49) Gelfand,B (2733)-Ivanchuk,V (2729)
Odessa 2007}) 14... Bc4 $1 {Black continues to pursue piece trades} 15. Bxc4
Nxc4 16. Qa4+ c6 17. Qxb4 Nxe3 18. Kf2 Nc2 $17 {0-1 (32) Morozevich,A (2770)
-Ivanchuk,V (2769) Astana 2012}) (12. Bd2 Nc4 13. Qc2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 e6 15. Rc1
{0-1 (57) Rodshtein,M (2642)-Ponomariov,R (2734) Istanbul 2012} Bxc5 $5 16.
Rxc5 a6 17. O-O Qd8 18. Rfc1 O-O 19. Bb1 Ne7 20. Nf4 Bc6 $13) (12. O-O e6 13.
Qc2 Nb4 $132) (12. Nf4 e6 13. Be3 Bc4 $1 $132) 12... e6 13. Qc2 (13. O-O $2
Nxd4 $1 $17) 13... Bxc5 14. Qxc5 (14. dxc5 Nd7 15. f4 Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bf3 17. Be3
(17. Rxg7 Qd8 $132 {[%cal Gd8h4]}) 17... g6 18. O-O-O Ne7 19. Be4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4
{0-1 (47) Morozevich,A (2769)-Nakamura,H (2775) Moscow 2012} c6 $17) 14... Qd7
{Black plans to rearrange his pieces by placing the knight on e7 and bishop on
c6, which will then allow him to pursue the trade of light-squared bishops by
means of ...Bb5} 15. b4 $6 {this move does little more than weaken White's
queenside, the light-squares in particular} (15. Be3 $5 {preparing Nf4 should
be met by} a6 16. Nf4 Ne7 (16... Nc4 $2 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Qxc4
$16) 17. O-O (17. Nh5 O-O-O 18. Nxg7 Rhg8 19. Nh5 Rxg2 $15) 17... Bc6 18. Rfd1
(18. Bf2 Bb5 $11) 18... Nbd5 (18... Bb5 19. Be4 $14) 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bf2 Qe7
21. Qc2 h5 22. b4 g5 23. Be4 g4 24. f4 h4 $40) (15. O-O a6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gd5c6,
Gc6b5] This is the most effective way of carrying out Petrosian's idea of ...
Ne7 followed by ...Bc6 as it forces the White queen to retreat to a more
passive square} (15... Qe7 16. Qc2 Qd7 17. Bd2 Ne7 18. Rac1 Bc6 19. Be3 Nbd5
20. Bf2 Bb5 $11 {0-1 (63) Bukic,E (2495)-Petrosian,T (2610) Banja Luka 1979})
16. Qc2 (16. Bg5 $2 Nc4 $1 17. Bxc4 b6 $19 {is a nice way of trapping the
White queen, as it occured in the game 0-1 Sanikidze,T (2585) -Rasmussen,A 
(2496) Istanbul 2012}) (16. Qc3 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Gd5c6,Gc6b5] Black continues
with the thematic plan. White only way to create real problems is to stop it
with} 17. b3 Bc6 18. a4 Nbd5 19. Qd2 f5 (19... h5 $5 20. Ba3 h4 21. h3 Nf5 $132
) 20. exf6 gxf6 21. Ng3 f5 22. Re1 Rg8 23. Qe2 Rg6 24. Nh5 O-O-O $13) 16... Ne7
(16... Nxd4 $5 {is another interesting try} 17. Nxd4 Bc4 18. Be3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3
c5 20. Rfd1 cxd4 21. Bxd4 Nd5 {Despite the evaluation of the engine with such
knight on d5, Black can't be worse,} 22. Bc5 Qb5 23. Qd4 Rc8 24. b4 (24. Rac1
b6 25. Bd6 (25. Bxb6 Rxc1 26. Rxc1 O-O {with compensation}) 25... Kd7 $13)
24... b6 25. Bd6 Qc4 26. Qf2 Qc2 27. Qg3 Qg6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (37) Wojtaszek, R 
(2700)-Yudin,S (2548) Loo 2013}) 17. Be3 Bc6 18. Bf2 Ba4 (18... Bb5 19. Be4 $14
{this is White's best way to respond against the idea of ...Bb5}) 19. b3 Bb5
20. Be4 Nbd5 21. Rfc1 Bxe2 $1 $146 {There is no reason to believe that the
bishop pair will be better than the knight given Black's powerful grip on the
center} (21... f5 22. exf6 gxf6 23. Nc3 $14 {1-0 (61) Wojtaszek,R (2736)-Zhang,
Z (2637) Baku 2016}) 22. Qxe2 f5 23. exf6 gxf6 24. Re1 Kf7 25. Rac1 h5 26. Qc4
Rag8 $13 {Black's powerful outpost on d5 makes his knights just as strong as
White's bishops}) (15. Nf4 $2 Na4 $17 {and White loses the d4-pawn}) 15... a6
16. Qc2 (16. Bg5 $2 Nc4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc5] 0-1 (52) Razuvaev,Y (2535)-Yakovich,
Y (2440) Sochi 1986}) (16. O-O $2 Nc4 17. b5 axb5 18. Qxb5 N6xe5 19. Qxd7+ Nxd7
$17 {0-1 (82) Dreev,A (2689)-Komarov,D (2565) playchess.com INT 2004}) 16...
Ne7 17. Bg5 Bc6 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. O-O Bb5 $11 {0-1 (63) Arencibia Rodriguez,W 
(2425)-Yakovich, Y (2470) Bayamo 1990} *

